0 1 0 'Blade runner' Pistorius charged with murder of model girlfriend - CNN
0 1 1 comPretoria, South Africa A beloved model is dead, those who knew her are in mourning, and one of the world's most admired Olympians is charged with her murder after a Valentine's Day shooting in South Africa
0 1 2 Oscar Pistorius, a Paralympic runner who blazed new terrain by competing in last summer's Olympics, is accused of killing his girlfriend, Reeva Steenkamp
0 1 3 A shooting took place inside his upscale home in Pretoria, South Africa, early Thursday, and only the two of them were there at the time, police said
0 1 4 Shock waves from the incident quickly reverberated across the world, casting a shadow over the man known as the "Blade Runner" for his achievements on prosthetic limbs
0 1 5 Pistorius will be named officially as the suspect when he appears in court Friday, in keeping with South African law
0 1 6 Authorities have already announced that the suspect is Pistorius' age
0 1 7 Investigators gave no motive for the alleged killing
0 1 8 Read more: 'Blade runner' Pistorius: Track hero at center of shooting probe"Previous incidents" at the home, police sayPolice were alerted to the shooting by neighbors, and residents had "heard things earlier," spokeswoman Denise Beukes said
0 1 9 A police spokeswoman said there had been "previous incidents" at the home, including "allegations of a domestic nature
0 1 10 "They did not detail what those may be
0 1 11 Pistorius was arrested and accused of common assault in 2009, but the case was thrown out because of a lack of evidence, police told CNN on Thursday
0 1 12 That incident involved Pistorius allegedly slamming a door during a party, and a piece of the door fell off and hit someone, said Capt
0 1 13 Marissa Van der Merwe of South African police
0 1 14 Police are not aware of any prior incidents between Pistorius and Steenkamp, Van der Merwe said
0 1 15 Some South African media outlets suggested Pistorius may have mistaken Steenkamp for an intruder
0 1 16 South Africa has a high crime rate, and many homeowners keep weapons to ward off intruders
0 1 17 Beukes said those reports did not come from police
0 1 18 There did not appear to be signs of forced entry at the home, she added
0 1 19 "This is a very quiet area, and this is a secure estate," Beukes said
0 1 20 A pistol was recovered at the scene, police said
0 1 21 In November 2011, Pistorius tweeted a photo of himself at a gun range, and wrote that he had "a 96% headshot over 300m from 50 shots!Bam!"Pistorius cooperating with policePistorius has made no public statement
0 1 22 His spokeswoman Kate Silvers said the athlete is "assisting the police with their investigation but there will be no further comment until matters become clearer later today
0 1 23 "Police also said Pistorius is cooperating
0 1 24 He arrived Thursday at a police station in Pretoria
0 1 25 Beukes said the state will oppose bail
0 1 26 That means the 26-year-old, who was among the men featured in People magazine's "Sexiest Man Alive" issue, could be behind bars, at least temporarily
0 1 27 Pistorius is not being brought to court Thursday because the public prosecutor needs more time to prepare the case, police spokeswoman Katlego Mogale told CNN
0 1 28 A model's life violently cut shortSteenkamp, 29, had been looking forward to Valentine's Day, encouraging her Twitter followers to "get excited" for the holiday
0 1 29 On Wednesday, she tweeted, "It's a beautiful day!Make things happen
0 1 30 Starting my day off with a yummy healthy shake from my boo," followed by a smiley face
0 1 31 "Boo" is a term for boyfriend
0 1 32 "She was the kindest, sweetest human being; an angel on earth and will be sorely missed," Capacity Relations, the agency that represented her, wrote on Twitter
0 1 33 She was "just a great, fun presence of a person," said Hagen Engler, former editor of the magazine FHM
0 1 34 He described her as "a bikini model, beautiful, gorgeous girl" with a "wicked" sense of humor
0 1 35 She understood the industry and was intelligent and fun to work with, he said
0 1 36 Pistorius' father, Henke, told the South African Broadcasting Corp
0 1 37  his son was "sad at the moment
0 1 38 ""I don't know nothing
0 1 39 It will be extremely obnoxious and rude to speculate," the father said
0 1 40 "I don't know the facts
0 1 41 "Nike pulls adNike pulled an ad featuring Pistorius from its website Thursday
0 1 42 The ad showed Pistorius taking off for a run, and contained the words" I am the bullet in the chamber
0 1 43 "The company issued a statement expressing "sympathy and condolences to the families concerned following this tragic incident
0 1 44 "The company added that it will not comment further, noting that the situation is a police matter
0 1 45 Other Pistorius sponsors -- including prosthetics manufacturer Ossur, British Telecom, and Oakley, which makes sunglasses and other products -- expressed condolences and said they had no further comment at this time
0 1 46 Fashion company Thierry Mugler had no comment
0 1 47 As Olympian, Pistorius faced controversyPistorius, a double amputee, competed against able-bodied runners during the London Olympics, triggering controversy as some said the prosthetic limbs gave him an advantage
0 1 48 His legs were amputated below the knee when he was a toddler because of a bone defect
0 1 49 He runs on special carbon fiber blades
0 1 50 Pistorius was initially refused permission to enter the Olympics, but he hired a legal team to prove that his artificial limbs did not give him an unfair advantage -- and was allowed to compete
0 1 51 While he did not win a medal, his presence on the track was lauded by many people around the world as an example of victory over adversity and dedication to a goal
0 1 52 He smashed a Paralympic record to win the men's 400m T44 in the final athletics event of the 2012 Games
0 1 53 In an October interview with CNN's "Piers Morgan Tonight," Pistorius discussed the "massive blessing" of inspiring people around the world
0 1 54 "Being an international sportsman, there's a lot of responsibility that comes with that, so having to toggle that and remembering, you know, that there are kids out there, especially, that look up to you -- it's definitely something that you need to keep at the back of your mind
0 1 55 "In December: Pistorius speaks to Piers Morgan about being a role modelCNN's Nkepile Mabuse reported from Pretoria; CNN's Josh Levs and Faith Karimi reported from Atlanta
0 1 56 CNN's Richard Allen Greene, Felicia Taylor, and Marilia Brocchetto contributed to this report

1 1 0 'Blade Runner' Pistorius, charged with murder, sobs in court - CNN
1 1 1 comPretoria, South Africa An international sports icon is behind bars
1 1 2 His girlfriend is dead
1 1 3 And South Africa is grappling with one of its most notorious killings in recent memory
1 1 4 Olympic runner Oscar Pistorius, known as Blade Runner for his lightning-fast prosthetic legs, shook and sobbed Friday when a judge officially charged him with killing his girlfriend on Valentine's Day
1 1 5 Wearing a dark suit, he buried his head in his hands at a packed courtroom in Pretoria
1 1 6 Prosecutors said they plan to charge the 26-year-old with premeditated murder
1 1 7 Pistorius rejects the murder allegation "in the strongest terms," his agent, Peet Vanzuyl, told CNN
1 1 8 His girlfriend, model Reeva Steenkamp, was found in a pool of blood at Pistorius' home Thursday in an upscale neighborhood in the capital
1 1 9 READ: Pistorius' girlfriend killed on Valentine's Day she was looking forward toNeighbors alerted authorities to the early morning shooting, saying they had "heard things earlier," according to police spokeswoman Denise Beukes
1 1 10 She did not clarify what the neighbors reported they heard
1 1 11 The track star was arrested the same day
1 1 12 Steenkamp's killing rattled South Africa, not only for the fame factor, but also because the country is grappling with a disturbing problem -- 71% of women report that they've been the victim of sexual abuse
1 1 13 Just in the past few weeks, 17-year-old Anene Booyson died after being gang-raped and mutilated in the tiny tourist town of Bredasdorp, two hours southeast of Cape Town
1 1 14 Booyson's death inspired this week's nationwide rape awareness day dubbed Black Friday
1 1 15 The day before she was killed, Steenkamp retweeted a message on Twitter in support of Black Friday
1 1 16 READ: Pistorius case and the plague of violence against womenWhile police have not discussed a possible motive for the model's killing, local media reported that Pistorius had mistaken his girlfriend for an intruder
1 1 17 South Africa has a high crime rate, and many homeowners keep weapons to protect themselves from intruders
1 1 18 But Beukes, the police spokeswoman, stressed that this scenario did not come from authorities
1 1 19 There was no evidence of forced entry at the home, she said
1 1 20 Police said there had been previous "allegations of a domestic nature" at his house, but they did not elaborate
1 1 21 Investigators found a pistol at the scene
1 1 22 South Africa's gun debateOn a larger stage, Steenkamp's killing has given gun control advocates a spotlight to push for stricter laws
1 1 23 Gunpolicy
1 1 24 org says there are just under 6 million licensed firearms in South Africa, a country of 50 million people
1 1 25 "There are 1
1 1 26 5 million gun owners -- about 3
1 1 27 5 million guns in civilians hands," said Alan Storey, chairman of Gun Free South Africa
1 1 28 Most of the victims of gun homicides are between the ages 20 and 30, he said
1 1 29 READ: Time "How tough are South Africa's gun laws?"South Africa has passed tough legislation that includes a requirement for a thorough background check for prospective gun owners
1 1 30 The check includes spouses and partners, and is repeated every few years, he said
1 1 31 WATCH: Police probe shooting at Pistorius home"People acquire guns believing they are more safe 
1 1 32 
1 1 33 
1 1 34  but they place themselves at great risk," Storey said
1 1 35 "We've made airplanes a gun-free zone
1 1 36 We need to bring that logic down to earth
1 1 37 "But the South African Gunowners' Association, a popular gun lobby group, has said citizens have the right to protect themselves from increasingly violent crimes
1 1 38 "There are already more than enough laws and regulations to control the possession of firearms by private citizens," it says on its website
1 1 39 "Fewer and less complex laws reasonably, yet properly, applied could achieve the required objective
1 1 40 "One issue in South Africa is stolen guns
1 1 41 Guns are often stolen from home, reports show, but also from the police
1 1 42 Statistics suggest that 18,196 police firearms have been lost or stolen during the five-year period beginning April 1 2005 to March 31 2011
1 1 43 From hero to murder suspectBeyond the violence, South Africans struggled with the idea that they've lost a hero, an athlete who embodied what it meant to overcome incredible physical odds
1 1 44 When Pistorius was a toddler, his legs were amputated below the knees because of a bone defect
1 1 45 Earning the nickname "Blade Runner," Pistorius runs on special carbon fiber blades
1 1 46 He became the first Paralympic sprinter competing against able-bodied athletes at the London Olympics last year
1 1 47 His face became a fixture on billboards across the nation, and he and Steenkamp were photographed at high-profile celebrity events and around town
1 1 48 READ: Oscar Pistorius, an inspiration and a questionHours after the news of his arrest, some of the billboards started coming down
1 1 49 His sponsors also pulled away
1 1 50 Nike removed an ad featuring him from its website showing him taking off for a run with the words "I am the bullet in the chamber
1 1 51 "READ: Nike's bullet ad with Pistorius backfiresOther Pistorius sponsors -- including prosthetics manufacturer Ossur, British Telecom, and Oakley, which makes sunglasses and other products -- expressed condolences and said they had no further comment
1 1 52 The sports icon appeared in headlines across the nation, overshadowing the State of the Union address by President Jacob Zuma
1 1 53 "Golden Boy Loses Shine," read a headline on the front page of the Sowetan
1 1 54 The Pretoria court postponed Pistorius' bail hearing to Tuesday and ordered him to remain in custody until then
1 1 55 Prosecutors said they will argue that he committed premeditated murder
1 1 56 Authorities said they will oppose bail, but did not provide their reasons for the decision
1 1 57 He shattered barriersThe double amputee's London Olympics appearance brought controversy, as some said the prosthetic limbs gave him an advantage
1 1 58 Pistorius was initially refused permission to enter the Olympics, but he hired a legal team to prove that his artificial limbs did not give him an unfair advantage, and he was allowed to compete
1 1 59 While he did not win a medal, his presence on the track was lauded as an example of victory over adversity and dedication to a goal
1 1 60 READ: 'Barbaric' whipping of horse in Pistorius raceIn the 2012 Paralympics, held a few weeks after the Olympics, he smashed a record to win the men's 400-meter in the final athletics event of the Games
1 1 61 In October, he discussed the "massive blessing" of inspiring people around the world
1 1 62 "Being an international sportsman, there's a lot of responsibility that comes with that," he told CNN's "Piers Morgan Tonight
1 1 63 "PHOTOS: The career of Oscar PistoriusCNN's Robyn Curnow reported from Pretoria, and Ashley Fantz and Faith Karim from Atlanta
1 1 64 CNN's Josh Levs, Marilia Brocchetto and Emily Smith contributed to this report
1 1 65

1 2 879 ['pistoriu', 'weep', 'court', 'prosecutor', 'seek', 'premedit', 'murder', 'charg']
2 1 0 Few details, plenty of questions as Pistorius disputes murder charge - CNN
2 1 1 comPretoria, South Africa Olympic and Paralympic runner Oscar Pistorius on Sunday canceled his appearance in five upcoming races, days after being charged with murder in the shooting death of his girlfriend in South Africa
2 1 2 The move is meant to help Pistorius focus on the legal proceedings and "help and support all those involved as they try to come to terms with this very difficult and distressing situation," said Peet Van Zyl of Pistorius' management company, In Site Athlete Management
2 1 3 The Valentine's Day shooting has stunned South Africa, where Pistorius is a national hero
2 1 4 Universal admiration for his sports achievements turned to shock, and with only scant details being made public, the questions are swirling
2 1 5 What transpired in Pistorius' upscale Pretoria home?What led to the killing of his girlfriend, Reeva Steenkamp, a platinum-haired model gearing up for her reality television debut?And why on Valentine's Day?In a packed courtroom in Pretoria, the man nicknamed "Blade Runner," for his lightning-fast prosthetic legs, held his head in his hands and wept
2 1 6 His loud sobs shook his body uncontrollably
2 1 7 "As you can imagine our entire family is devastated, we are in a state of total shock," said his uncle, Arnold Pistorius, in a written statement
2 1 8 "All of us saw at first hand how close she had become to Oscar during that time and how happy they were
2 1 9 ""We have no doubt there is no substance to the allegation and that the State's own case, including its own forensic evidence, strongly refutes any possibility of a premeditated murder or indeed any murder at all
2 1 10 "Pistorius, 26, also rejected the murder allegation "in the strongest terms," his agent said in a statement
2 1 11 'Medals are just medals'But Saturday, two days after Steenkamp's death, some South Africans remained puzzled over his alleged involvement
2 1 12 Despite the fact that he is innocent until proven guilty, some said the allegation has tainted his image
2 1 13 "I was very shocked
2 1 14 A mother lost a daughter
2 1 15 I was not expecting anything like this from someone like him," said Nondumiso Mlondo, who lives in Durban
2 1 16 "Everybody is still talking about it
2 1 17 Just think of those young kids who want to be like him, who are looking up to him
2 1 18 After his Olympic success, we were hoping for something bigger for him this year 
2 1 19 
2 1 20 
2 1 21  look what has happened
2 1 22 "Citizens carried on heated discussions in buses, bars, barber shops
2 1 23 "People are saying 
2 1 24 
2 1 25  why do stars make a point of screwing up when they are doing so well?"Mlondo asked
2 1 26 "Medals are just medals 
2 1 27 
2 1 28 
2 1 29  I don't care whether he has hundreds of them, he should be held accountable
2 1 30 "Opinion: Pistorius case and the plague of violence against women'Life goes on'But for others, the shock was ebbing
2 1 31 "Life goes on," said Rufaz Mavhure, who lives in Woodmead, a commercial suburb of Johannesburg
2 1 32 "It was a shock to the nation when we first heard it 
2 1 33 
2 1 34 
2 1 35  but it has worn off," he said
2 1 36 "We have sobered up -- even though people will still question why
2 1 37 "The allegation was a major fall from grace for a man who made history last year by becoming the first double-amputee runner to compete in the able-bodied Olympic Games in London
2 1 38 Meanwhile, South Africa's national broadcaster aired a reality TV show featuring Steenkamp discussing her exit from the taped program, on which she was a contestant
2 1 39 "I'm going home with sort of a sweet taste in my mouth
2 1 40 I don't have any regrets
2 1 41 I don't have any bitterness," she said
2 1 42 "I'm going to miss you all so much and I love you very very much
2 1 43 "The decision to air the program took "much deliberation," and that "this week's episode will be dedicated to Reeva's memory," Executive producer Samantha Moon said
2 1 44 A fallen heroWhen Pistorius was 11 months old, his legs were amputated below the knees because he was missing the fibulae in his legs
2 1 45 He runs on special carbon fiber blades, hence the nickname
2 1 46 A few weeks after the Olympics, he smashed a record to win the men's 400-meter in the 2012 Paralympic Games
2 1 47 Images of his sports feats flashed across the screens at the time
2 1 48 But by Thursday, it was a jarringly different story
2 1 49 Pictures of his walk to a police car, his head covered by a sweatshirt, flashed across television screens worldwide
2 1 50 Then there was his court appearance 24 hours later, grim-faced and sobbing uncontrollably
2 1 51 Prosecutors planned to upgrade the charge to premeditated murder
2 1 52 Nike's bullet ad with Pistorius backfiresA nation, joltedSteenkamp's killing rattled South Africa, which is grappling with the aftermath of the recent murder of 17-year-old Anene Booyson -- a case that has put a spotlight on violence against women
2 1 53 Booyson died after she was gang-raped and mutilated in Bredasdorp, a tiny tourist town southeast of Capetown
2 1 54 While police have not discussed a possible motive for the 29-year-old model's killing, local media reported that Pistorius had mistaken his girlfriend for an intruder
2 1 55 But South African authorities stressed that the scenario did not come from them, and said there was no evidence of forced entry at the home
2 1 56 Police found her in a pool of blood before dawn Thursday after neighbors in the gated community alerted them
2 1 57 Investigators found a 9mm pistol at the scene
2 1 58 Renewed calls for stricter gun lawsSouth Africa has a high crime rate, and many homeowners keep weapons to ward off intruders
2 1 59 Groups renewed calls for stricter gun laws in the nation after this week's killing
2 1 60 "There are 1
2 1 61 5 million gun owners -- about 3
2 1 62 5 million guns in civilians hands," said Alan Storey, chairman of Gun Free South Africa
2 1 63 Most of the victims of gun homicides in the nation of 50 million people are between the ages 20 and 30, he said
2 1 64 South Africa has passed tough legislation that includes a requirement for a thorough background check for prospective gun owners
2 1 65 The check includes spouses and partners, and is repeated every few years, he said
2 1 66 "People acquire guns believing they are more safe 
2 1 67 
2 1 68 
2 1 69  but they place themselves at greater risk," Storey said
2 1 70 "We've made airplanes a gun-free zone
2 1 71 We need to bring that logic down to earth
2 1 72 "But the South African Gunowners' Association, a popular gun lobby group, has said citizens have the right to protect themselves from increasingly violent crimes
2 1 73 "There are already more than enough laws and regulations to control the possession of firearms by private citizens," it says on its website
2 1 74 "Fewer and less complex laws reasonably, yet properly, applied could achieve the required objective
2 1 75 "Postponed bail hearingBeyond the violence, South Africans struggled with the idea that they've lost a hero, an athlete who defied incredible physical odds to become a global star
2 1 76 His face became a fixture on billboards across the nation, some of which started coming down after his arrest
2 1 77 The Pretoria court postponed Pistorius' bail hearing to Tuesday and ordered him to remain in custody until then
2 1 78 Prosecutors said they will argue that he committed premeditated murder
2 1 79 Authorities said they will oppose bail, but did not provide their reasons for the decision
2 1 80 CNN's Robyn Curnow reported from Pretoria and Faith Karimi from Atlanta
2 1 81

3 1 0 Oscar Pistorius' brother Carl accused in 2010 death - CNN
3 1 1 comJohannesburg As Olympic icon Oscar Pistorius faces a murder trial for shooting his girlfriend, his older brother is also charged in the death of a woman
3 1 2 Carl Pistorius is accused in the 2010 death of a female motorcyclist, Pistorius family attorney Kenny Oldwage said
3 1 3 Culpable homicide refers to "unlawful negligent killing," South African police say
3 1 4 Prosecutors say Carl Pistorius was driving recklessly in Vanderbijlpark, South Africa, when he crashed with the motorcyclist in the daytime
3 1 5 Oldwage disputes allegations that his client was driving recklessly and said the motorcyclist rode into Carl Pistorius' vehicle
3 1 6 "Carl deeply regrets the accident
3 1 7 Blood tests conducted by the police at the time proved that he had not been under the influence of alcohol, confirming that it was a tragic road accident after the deceased collided with Carl's car," a statement from the Pistorius family said
3 1 8 The motorcyclist died in a hospital a couple of days after the accident, Oldwage said
3 1 9 Carl Pistorius was initially scheduled to go on trial Thursday -- during the middle of his brother's four-day bail hearing
3 1 10 The trial has been rescheduled for the end of March
3 1 11 His case could be over before his brother's murder trial is scheduled to start in June
3 1 12 Carl Pistorius was a fixture at his younger brother's bail hearing last week, handing Oscar tissues as the 26-year-old sobbed uncontrollably in court
3 1 13 Oscar Pistorius, the double-amputee sprinter known as the "Blade Runner," is charged with premeditated murder in the death of his girlfriend, model Reeva Steenkamp
3 1 14 Prosecutors say the Olympian killed her after a heated argument in the early morning hours of Valentine's Day
3 1 15 Pistorius says he thought Steenkamp, 29, was an intruder
3 1 16 After a four-day, emotionally wrenching bail hearing, the track star was granted bail Friday
3 1 17 As part of his conditions for release, Oscar Pistorius cannot return to his home, where the shooting happened; must surrender his passport; and can't go near an airport
3 1 18 It's unknown whether Oscar Pistorius will be in court to support his brother during his trial
3 1 19 CNN's Karen Smith and Josh Levs contributed to this report

4 1 0 South Africa judge lifts travel ban on Oscar Pistorius - CNN
4 1 1 comPretoria, South Africa South African track star Oscar Pistorius, charged with murder in the shooting death of girlfriend Reeva Steenkamp, is once more allowed to travel overseas after a judge lifted a bail condition Thursday restricting his movements
4 1 2 Judge Bert Bam said that Pistorius' passport could be held by his attorney, Barry Roux, instead of the court and that he was entitled to use it to travel outside South Africa
4 1 3 Bam said he saw no reason why Pistorius "should be forbidden to leave South Africa if invited to compete overseas
4 1 4 "Pistorius should report his itinerary a week before leaving and hand his travel documents back over to his lawyer within 24 hours of returning to South Africa, Bam said at Pretoria's North Gauteng High Court
4 1 5 Pistorius not suicidal, family saysThe athlete may also now drink alcohol and return home to the scene of the crime, he ruled
4 1 6 Bam said the magistrate who imposed the original bail restrictions last month had not included the prohibition on Pistorius returning to his home or a requirement that he report to a police station twice a week in the written court order he signed
4 1 7 This means those provisions, which the magistrate only mentioned verbally in court, should be ignored, Bam said
4 1 8 The new order represents a victory for the athlete's legal team, which went to court to request more lenient terms for his bail
4 1 9 Not everyone surprised about Pistorius' fall from graceThe lifting of the travel ban could mean that the Olympic and Paralympic sprinter would return to international competition ahead of his trial
4 1 10 If Pistorius qualifies for the Moscow World Championships in August, "then on the basis of the 'innocent until proven guilty' principle, he would be free to run," Yannis Nikolaou, communications manager for the International Association of Athletics Federations, told CNN via e-mail
4 1 11 Invitations are at the discretion of meeting organizers, not the IAAF, he said
4 1 12 The IAAF will not comment on the case against Pistorius, he added
4 1 13 Premeditated murder chargeThe athlete's lawyers argued in their appeal filing that since Pistorius was not considered a flight risk, the restrictions on his travel were unnecessary
4 1 14 They also argued that since alcohol and substance abuse were not factors in the case, the ban on their use was not warranted
4 1 15 Pistorius had no desire to use alcohol or illegal drugs, they added
4 1 16 Authorities charged Pistorius with premeditated murder after he shot Steenkamp in the bathroom of his Pretoria home on February 14
4 1 17 Pistorius, who spent eight days in jail before being freed on bail on February 22, did not attend Thursday's hearing
4 1 18 State prosecutor Gerrie Nel told the court Thursday that he plans to serve Pistorius with an indictment on June 4
4 1 19 No trial date has yet been set
4 1 20 Pistorius, known as the "Blade Runner" for competing on carbon fiber blades fitted to the stumps of his amputated legs, says he thought Steenkamp was an intruder
4 1 21 Prosecutors argue that he intentionally killed her after a loud argument
4 1 22 READ MORE: Pistorius case brings South Africa gun culture to global spotlightREAD MORE: Not everyone surprised at Oscar Pistorius' fall from graceCNN's Nkepile Mabuse reported from Pretoria and Laura Smith-Spark wrote in London
4 1 23 Harry Reekie contributed to this report
4 1 24

5 1 0 Police: Lead detective in Oscar Pistorius case faces attempted murder chargesPRETORIA, South Africa (AP) — The head of South African police appointed a new lead investigator Thursday in the Oscar Pistorius premeditated murder case after it came to light that previous murder charges against the detective in question had been reinstated, potentially another damaging blow to the prosecution
5 1 1 National Commissioner Riah Phiyega says Lt
5 1 2  Gen
5 1 3  Vinesh Moonoo will take over the investigation
5 1 4 Phiyega says the Pistorius case "shall receive attention at the national level" and Moonoo will "gather a team of highly skilled and experience detectives
5 1 5 "She says Moonoo is the South Africa police's "top detective
5 1 6 "Prosecutors said they were unaware of the charges against veteran detective Hilton Botha when they put him on the stand in court Tuesday and Wednesday to explain why Pistorius, the double-amputee Olympic and Paralympic runner should not be given bail in the Valentine's Day shooting death of his girlfriend
5 1 7 Prosecutors say Pistorius intentionally killed model Reeva Steenkamp and have charged him with premeditated murder
5 1 8 Pistorius says he mistook Steenkamp for an intruder and that the shooting was accidental
5 1 9 MORE: Detective a blow to prosecution caseDRUG TESTING: Case brings issue to light againPolice Brig
5 1 10 Neville Malila told the Associated Press that Botha — who gave testimony in the Pistorius bail hearing on Wednesday — is scheduled to appear in court in May on seven counts of attempted murder related to an incident in October 2011 when Botha and two other police officers fired at a minibus they were trying to stop
5 1 11 Malila said police had learned Wednesday, the same day that Botha appeared in court to oppose Pistorius' bail application, that the charges against Botha and the two others had been reinstated by the Director of Public Prosecutions
5 1 12 They were initially dropped following the shooting incident
5 1 13 Malila said police were now waiting for details from the Botha case file from the public prosecutor
5 1 14 South Africa's National Prosecuting Authority acknowledged the timing of the attempted murder charges against Botha is "totally weird
5 1 15 "In the state case against the Olympic athlete, Botha offered often confused testimony and conceded that nothing in Pistorius' account of the Steenkamp shooting contradicted the police's version
5 1 16 On Thursday, magistrate Desmond Nair questioned Botha over delays in processing records from phones found in Pistorius' house
5 1 17 Botha was the lead investigator in an assault claim against Pistorius in 2009
5 1 18 Pistorius' lawyers said police arrested the athlete and held him overnight at a police station and said they will pursue a lawsuit against police for wrongful arrest
5 1 19 The current case against Pistorius, which is still only in a bail hearing, has riveted much of the world
5 1 20 Pistorius, the 26-year-old known as the Blade Runner for his carbon-fiber running prosthetic legs, says he fired shots through the locked door of a toilet enclosed inside his bathroom because he thought there was an intruder in there
5 1 21 Steenkamp was hit three times, in the head, right elbow and right hip, police say, and prosecutors argue Pistorius intended to kill his 29-year-old girlfriend after a fight in the early hours of Valentine's Day
5 1 22 PHOTOS: OSCAR PISTORIUS MURDER TRIALCopyright 2013 The Associated Press
5 1 23 All rights reserved
5 1 24 This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed
5 1 25

6 1 0 Botha, former Pistorius detective, off police force - CNN
6 1 1 comHilton Botha, the former lead detective in the Oscar Pistorius murder case, cited "private reasons" for resigning from the police force, South African Police spokesman Brig
6 1 2 Neville Malila said Thursday
6 1 3 Botha was pulled from the Pistorius case last month after prosecutors reinstated attempted murder charges against him in a 2011 case
6 1 4 The 22-year South African Police veteran is accused of chasing and firing on a minibus full of people while drunk
6 1 5 He is charged with seven counts of attempted murder
6 1 6 Opinion: Not everyone surprised at Oscar Pistorius' fall from gracePistorius, the 26-year-old double amputee track star, is accused in the killing of his girlfriend, Reeva Steenkamp, 29, last month
6 1 7 Botha, the first officer on the scene of the Valentine's Day shooting, handed in his resignation Wednesday, Malila said
6 1 8 "We are not going into the reasons," Malila said
6 1 9 "He has indicated to us it is for private reasons
6 1 10 "His removal from the high-profile murder case came just days after his testimony at a bail hearing for Pistorius that included admissions that police could have contaminated the crime scene and failed to properly catalog evidence
6 1 11 The sprinter said in an affidavit that he thought an intruder was hiding in a toilet room inside the bathroom of his Pretoria home
6 1 12 He fired into the room in a fit of terror before realizing the person inside was Steenkamp, Pistorius said
6 1 13 During the three-day bail hearing, held in a dark, stuffy Pretoria courtroom, defense attorney Barry Roux hammered away at the credibility of Botha and the entire police investigation
6 1 14 Opinion: Pistorius case brings South Africa gun culture to spotlightHe argued that police had missed a bullet in the toilet of the bathroom where Steenkamp was shot and may have contaminated the crime scene by failing to wear protective foot covers
6 1 15 Botha told Roux that investigators didn't wear the booties because they'd run out
6 1 16 Bulelwa Makeke, the spokeswoman for South Africa's National Prosecuting Authority, said before the announcement of Botha's removal that the accusations against the investigator would be little more than a "speed bump" in the Pistorius case
6 1 17 The attempted murder charges against Botha had previously been withdrawn for additional investigation, but prosecutors decided last month to proceed, South African Police Service Commissioner Riah Phiyega said
6 1 18 Phiyega praised Botha, saying he is an experienced investigator who "has presented the case of the police well
6 1 19 "Botha was replaced by the department's most senior detective, Vinesh Moonoo, in a move Phiyega said positioned the department for a "long-haul" investigation of Steenkamp's killing
6 1 20 Uncle: Victim's family won't attend Oscar Pistorius' trial

7 1 0 Prosecutors to pursue premeditated murder charge against Oscar PistoriusPRETORIA, South Africa (AP) — Oscar Pistorius held his head in his hands and wept openly in court Friday as prosecutors said they would pursue a charge of premeditated murder against the Paralympic superstar
7 1 1 Pistorius was formally charged at Pretoria Magistrate's Court with one count of murder after his girlfriend, Reeva Steenkamp, a model and budding reality TV show participant, was shot multiple times and killed at Pistorius' upmarket home in the predawn hours of Thursday
7 1 2 Prosecutor Gerrie Nel said Friday in court it was premeditated murder, indicating the prosecution would file that more serious charge, upgraded from murder
7 1 3 The double-amputee athlete's arrest and murder charge had already left South Africa stunned after the blonde model's shooting death at Pistorius' house in a gated community in an eastern suburb of the South African capital, Pretoria
7 1 4 REACTION: Locals conflicted on PistoriusFollowing the hearing, Pistorius' family and his London management company issued a statement calling into question the criminal charge the 26-year-old athlete faces
7 1 5 "The alleged murder is disputed in the strongest terms," the statement read
7 1 6 The statement did not elaborate
7 1 7 The statement also said Pistorius wanted to "send his deepest sympathies to the family of Reeva
7 1 8 ""He would also like to express his thanks through us today for all the messages of support he has received — but as stated our thoughts and prayers today should be for Reeva and her family — regardless of the circumstances of this terrible, terrible tragedy," the statement read
7 1 9 Those who knew Pistorius, including a former girlfriend, weighed in on social media
7 1 10 Trish Taylor, mother of Pistorius' ex-girlfriend Samantha Taylor, wrote on Facebook: "I'm so glad Sammy is safe and out of the clutches of that man
7 1 11 "MORE: Pistorius leaves sponsors, fans dismayedSTEENKAMP: Model's heartbreaking final tweetsBut another ex-girlfriend, Jenna Edkins, defended the accused man Tuesday on Twitter
7 1 12 "All I am saying is let him speak, let his side be heard without jumping to conclusions," tweeted Jenna Edkins, an attractive, young blonde like all Pistorius' girlfriends
7 1 13 She offered "love and support" to the Pistorius family and tweeted: "I have dated Oscar on and off for 5 YEARS, NOT ONCE has he EVER lifted a finger to me or made me fear for my life
7 1 14 "Prosecutors said Friday that they would argue the history-making Olympic athlete — the first amputee to run at the Games — had planned Steenkamp's killing
7 1 15 It sent South Africans reeling further as their national hero and a global role model for people in overcoming adversity was set to face accusations that he intentionally gunned down his girlfriend
7 1 16 South Africa's tabloid Citizen newspaper had the headline "Blade gunner?"Friday morning, playing on double-amputee athlete Pistorius' well-known nickname of "Blade Runner" because of his carbon fiber running blades
7 1 17 Pistorius stood with his face in his hands as he broke down in tears in his first appearance at the Pretoria Magistrates' Court
7 1 18 Chief Magistrate Desmond Nasir delayed Pistorius' bail hearing until next Tuesday and Wednesday and ruled that Pistorius, 26, would be held at a police station in Pretoria until then
7 1 19 Police have said they oppose the granting of bail
7 1 20 Pistorius had solemnly entered the court wearing a gray suit and blue tie and initially appeared composed
7 1 21 When he broke down in tears, his brother, Carl, reached out a hand and placed it on his shoulder
7 1 22 Pistorius' father, Henke, was in the court as was sister Aimee
7 1 23 REACTION: Track and field community stunned, saddenedAD PULLED: Nike spot referred to him as bullet in chamberThe hot courtroom was jammed with more than 100 people, including numerous local and international journalists
7 1 24 More than 100 people packed into Courtroom C at the courthouse, including dozens of photographers and videographers, but Nasir ruled that no recordings of court proceedings would be allowed in the case
7 1 25 Police said Friday an autopsy on the victim was also taking place
7 1 26 Lt
7 1 27  Col
7 1 28  Katlego Mogale said the results of the autopsy would not be published
7 1 29 Pistorius earlier left a police station, his jacket completely covering his head as he got into a police vehicle
7 1 30 He was holding what appeared to be a white handkerchief in one hand as he was led by officers to a police van outside the Boschkop Police Station in eastern Pretoria, where he had been questioned on Thursday and had spent the night in custody
7 1 31 A policeman was also seen carrying a handgun in a plastic forensic bag outside the Boschkop station
7 1 32 It was believed to be the weapon used to shoot and kill Steenkamp
7 1 33 Police said the victim was shot four times at Pistorius' villa in a gated community
7 1 34 Officers found a 9 mm pistol inside the home
7 1 35 Pistorius made history at the London Olympics last year when he became the first double-amputee track athlete to compete at any Games
7 1 36 He didn't win a medal but did make the semifinals of the 400 meters and the final of the 4X400 relay, propelling the world's best-known Paralympian to the level of an international track star and one of the world's best-known sportsmen
7 1 37 But police hinted at a troubled lifestyle away from public scrutiny for the runner Thursday when they said there had previously been domestic incidents at Pistorius' home
7 1 38 PHOTOS: MORE ON REEVA STEENKAMPCopyright 2013 The Associated Press
7 1 39 All rights reserved
7 1 40 This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed

8 1 0 2 die, 305 survive after airliner crash lands at San Francisco airport - CNN
8 1 1 comAre you there?Send photosIt had been an uneventful 10-plus hour flight from Seoul, South Korea, approaching San Francisco's airport on a clear summer day
8 1 2 Then, in a few horrifying seconds, that calm was shattered
8 1 3 A fireball erupted after the Boeing 777 airliner hit the runway hard around 11:30 a
8 1 4 m
8 1 5 , rocked back and forth, spun around, shearing off the plane's tail
8 1 6 Scores of passengers and crew climbed out -- some jumping, others sliding down evacuation chutes as flames and smoke billowed from the aircraft's windows
8 1 7 Two people were found dead outside the plane, according to San Francisco fire Chief Joanne Hayes-White
8 1 8 "My understanding is that they were found on the runway," she said
8 1 9 The airline identified the dead girls as students Wang Linjia and Ye Mengyuan, both 16
8 1 10 Somehow, 305 others survived
8 1 11 Said San Francisco Mayor Ed Lee: "This could have been much worse
8 1 12 "Follow latest developments in the storyThat's an understandable sentiment for anyone who heard passenger and eyewitness accounts, or saw the distressing, distorted images showing what remained of Asiana Airlines Flight 214
8 1 13 Some photos painted an almost otherworldly scene -- like one posted online by David Eun of passengers walking from the burning plane
8 1 14 Some dragged their carry-on bags
8 1 15 One man held his hands steady to snap a picture
8 1 16 "I just crash landed at SFO," Eun wrote
8 1 17 "Tail ripped off
8 1 18 Most everyone seems fine
8 1 19 I'm ok
8 1 20 Surreal
8 1 21 
8 1 22 
8 1 23 "CNN iReporter Timothy Clark watched from an eighth-floor balcony of a nearby hotel
8 1 24 He recalled hearing a bang, seeing a "dust cloud," then seeing "people running from the plane, then flames
8 1 25 "Elliott Stone was one of them
8 1 26 He was "10 seconds away from being home" when the airplane dipped "kind of sharp," followed by another adjustment "and then just boom, the back end just hit and flies up in the air and everybody's head goes up to the ceiling
8 1 27 "The first announcement "was everybody calm," Stone said, but he and others unbuckled anyway
8 1 28 He told CNN he jumped out a door, before slides had deployed and before first responders had arrived
8 1 29 When they did, they saw some people climbing out of San Francisco Bay around the airport, Hayes-White said
8 1 30 Video taken soon after the crash and posted on YouTube showed dark gray smoke rising from the plane, which was upright on its belly, with no landing gear evident
8 1 31 Its roof was charred and, in spots, gone entirely
8 1 32 The back of the plane appeared to have been lopped off entirely
8 1 33 'I just crash landed at SFO
8 1 34 I'm ok
8 1 35 Surreal'Eunice Bird Rah provided CNN a photo shot by her father, showing flames and smoke bursting out of many of the aircraft's windows
8 1 36 Some 182 passengers and crew were being treated at Bay Area hospitals, with everything from spinal fractures to bumps and bruises, San Francisco deputy fire chief Dale Carnes said
8 1 37 Rah's father is one of the 123 people who escaped -- physically, at least -- uninjured, according to Carnes
8 1 38 He's "doing fine, thank God," his daughter said
8 1 39 It's not lost on her how horrible the whole scene was and how much more horrible it could have been
8 1 40 "It's heartbreaking," she said
8 1 41 No explanation yet on why this happenedInvestigators from Washington and Seoul are heading to northern California trying to answer a simple question
8 1 42 How did this happen?While the exact cause will take months to determine, the South Korean Transport Ministry said "the tail of the Asiana flight hit the runway and the aircraft veered to the left out of the runway
8 1 43 "Why this crash was survivableMembers of South Korea's Aviation and Railway Accident Investigation Board will travel to San Francisco, that agency said
8 1 44 They'll be joined by a "go-to" team from the United States' National Transportation Safety Board, led by chairman Deborah Hersman
8 1 45 Right now, they're not sure what they'll find, though a U
8 1 46 S
8 1 47  national security official has said there are no signs of terrorism
8 1 48 "We have not determined what the focus of this investigation is yet," Hersman said
8 1 49 "Everything is on the table at this point
8 1 50 "Watching from a nearby hotel, Anthony Castorani saw the plane touch the ground, then noticed a large plume of smoke
8 1 51 "You heard a pop and you immediately saw a large, brief fireball that came from underneath the aircraft," he told CNN
8 1 52 Kristina Stapchuck saw the dramatic scene unfold from her seat on a plane on the airport's tarmac
8 1 53 Soon after Flight 214 touched down, "it looked like the tires slipped a little bit and it rocked back," she told CNN
8 1 54 Parts of the plane began to break off as it rocked and then began to spin
8 1 55 "It all happened so suddenly," Stapchuck told CNN
8 1 56 Flight data recorders recovered from Asiana crash'Serious moment to give thanks'Well after the crash, debris extended through a large swath of the airport -- right up the water's edge
8 1 57 But the recovery will go well beyond that
8 1 58 There were 16 crew members on the flight, in addition to 291 passengers, according to Asiana Airlines
8 1 59 The manifest included 141 Chinese passengers, 77 South Koreans and 61 Americans
8 1 60 Carnes said that 49 of those treated at area hospitals were in "serious" condition
8 1 61 Fifty-two of them are at San Francisco General Hospital, including five patients in critical condition, hospital spokeswoman Rachael Kagan said
8 1 62 Another 45 have been treated at a Stanford University hospital, some of them suffering from "life-threatening injuries," said Dr
8 1 63  David Spain, the chief of trauma
8 1 64 "Many are critically injured," Lee stated Saturday evening
8 1 65 The crisis Saturday had trickle-down effects as well
8 1 66 At one point, flights destined for San Francisco International Airport were diverted to airports in Oakland, Sacramento, San Jose and Los Angeles, said Francis Zamora of San Francisco's emergency management department
8 1 67 Expert on crash: Shouldn't have been close to hitting seawallBy 3:30 p
8 1 68 m
8 1 69 , though, two of the San Francisco airport's four runways were open -- though the other two were still closed over eight hours later
8 1 70 The spotlight shone, too, on Asiana Airlines and the plane it received in 2006
8 1 71 One of South Korea's two major airlines, the other being Korean Air, it flies to 23 other countries
8 1 72 Many of the 25-year-old airline's flight go out of Incheon International Airport, which is the largest airport in South Korea and considered among the busiest in the world
8 1 73 What happened to the flight is one part of the story
8 1 74 But there are 307 more personal stories out there -- of people who were moments from wrapping up a long flight, but instead endured a nightmare
8 1 75 Some who weren't on board also have stories to tell -- whether they saw the horror from an aircraft, tried to track down family members, or counted their blessings in other ways
8 1 76 Sheryl Sandberg, Facebook's chief operating officer and author of the book "Lean In," is in the latter category
8 1 77 She was supposed to be on Flight 214, but switched to a United flight, arriving about 20 minutes before the Asiana flight crashed
8 1 78 "Serious moment to give thanks," she wrote on her own Facebook page
8 1 79 CNN's Mike M
8 1 80  Ahlers, Chelsea J
8 1 81  Carter, Rande Iaboni, K
8 1 82 J
8 1 83  Kwon, Kyung Lah, John King and Janet DiGiacomo contributed to this report

9 1 0 Investigators sift for reasons for Asiana crashFederal crash investigators are eager to interview the pilots and review the flight-data recorders that were recovered Saturday from the Asiana Airlines crash in San Francisco
9 1 1 The cockpit voice recorder and the flight-data recorder were each recovered hours after the crash and flown to Washington, D
9 1 2 C
9 1 3 , for examination by the National Transportation Safety Board
9 1 4 Deborah Hersman, the board chairman who traveled to the accident scene, said the recorders will provide hundreds of pieces of information about the flight in the moments and hours before the crash
9 1 5 "I am confident in the ability of our investigators to get to the bottom of this," Hersman said on NBC's Today show Sunday
9 1 6 "We need to take a look at it and see what it tells us
9 1 7 "STORY: Asiana CEO rules out mechanical failure in deadly crashFederal law-enforcement officials had initial conversations with the pilot, but the Federal Aviation Administration and NTSB still expect to speak with him within days, Hersman said
9 1 8 "There are a lot of systems to help support the pilots as they come into airports, especially busy commercial airports like this one in San Francisco," Hersman told CNN's State of the Union
9 1 9 "It's also about the pilots' recognition of the circumstances and what's going on, and so for them to be able to assess what's happening and make the right inputs to make sure they're in a safe situation," Hersman said
9 1 10 "That's what we expect from pilots
9 1 11 We want to understand what happened in this situation
9 1 12 "The tail of the Boeing 777 struck the end of the runway and fell off as it was landing
9 1 13 The plane struck the ground and spun around before coming to rest and burning
9 1 14 Two passengers died and 168 were injured; 307 passengers and crew were on board Flight 214
9 1 15 "What you can't see is the damage internally, and that is really striking," Hersman told CNN after visiting the plane
9 1 16 "And so I think when we look at this accident, we're very thankful that we didn't have more fatalities and serious injuries and we had so many survivors
9 1 17 "The president of Asiana, Yoon Young-doo, said at a televised news conference that it will take time to determine the cause of the crash
9 1 18 But when asked about the possibility of engine or mechanical problems, he said he doesn't believe they could have been the cause
9 1 19 Hersman said investigators needed to study the plane, the recorders and crew to learn what happened
9 1 20 "We really prefer to base statements on facts, and we've got to review the flight data recorder, the cockpit voice recorder, and document the scene before we draw any conclusions," Hersman told ABC's This Week
9 1 21 Contributing: The Associated Press

10 1 0 NTSB: Jet was traveling below target speed before crashSAN FRANCISCO — Asiana Airlines Flight 214 was traveling well below its target speed for landing when it crashed short of the runway Saturday, National Transportation Safety Board Chairman Deborah Hersman said at a briefing Sunday
10 1 1 "The speed was significantly below 137 knots, and we're not talking a few knots," she said
10 1 2 Asiana Airlines said the pilot in charge of landing the Boeing 777 was in training for flying that model of jet, and that this was his first flight into San Francisco at the controls of a 777, the Associated Press reported
10 1 3 "It was Lee Kang-kook's maiden flight to the airport with the jet
10 1 4 " a spokeswoman for Asiana Airlines who was not identified by name said, the news agency reported
10 1 5 It reported that he had flown Boeing 747 jets into San Francisco's airport previously, and was assisted on this flight by another pilot with more experience flying the 777
10 1 6 The plane was travelling "significantly below" its intended speed and its crew tried to abort the landing just seconds before it hit the seawall in front of the runway, the U
10 1 7 S
10 1 8  National Transportation Safety Board said on Sunday
10 1 9 "He has a lot of experience and previously flown to San Francisco on different planes including the B747
10 1 10 
10 1 11 
10 1 12  and he was assisted by another pilot who has more experience with the 777," the spokeswoman said
10 1 13 San Mateo County Coroner Robert Foucrault said Sunday that his office was investigating whether one of the two Chinese girls killed in the crash had been run over by a rescue vehicle
10 1 14 He said San Francisco Fire Department officials notified him at the site Saturday that one of the 16-year-olds may have been struck on the runway
10 1 15 An autopsy was to be completed Monday
10 1 16 Hersman provided details of what investigators found in their initial review of the plane's flight data and cockpit voice recorders: "The approach proceeds normally as they descend
10 1 17 There is no discussion of any aircraft anomalies or concerns with the approach
10 1 18 A call from one of the crewmembers to increase speed was made approximately seven seconds prior to impact
10 1 19 "The "stick shaker," which gives an audible and motion signal warning that the plane is flying too slowly and is about to stall, sounds "approximately four seconds prior to impact
10 1 20 "The pilot requested a "go-around" — to abort the landing, fly around the airport and try again, Hersman said
10 1 21 "A call to initiate a go-around occurred 1
10 1 22 5 seconds before impact," she said
10 1 23 STORY: San Francisco hospitals treat scores of crash survivorsSTORY: How do you get 300 people off a burning jet?STORY: Asiana crash deaths ID'd as 2 Chinese teensHersman said investigators will look at all possibilities for the cause of the crash, including pilot error
10 1 24 "Everything is on the table," she said
10 1 25 The flight crew had not been interviewed, a process that may take a few more days, she said
10 1 26 The engines will be dismantled to look for further clues
10 1 27 "What we need to do is corroborate the information we have on both the flight data recorder and the cockpit voice recorder" for a complete picture of what happened, she said, but the two devices appeared to "mirror" each other — that anomalies in the data appear to correspond to the pilots' actions
10 1 28 The CEO of Asiana Airlines said Sunday he had ruled out engine or mechanical problems in the crash
10 1 29 Yoon Young Doo, the president and chief executive of the airline, said at company headquarters Sunday, "I bow my head and sincerely apologize for causing concern to the passengers, families and our people
10 1 30 "For now, we acknowledge that there were no problems caused by the 777-200 plane or engines," Yoon said
10 1 31 He declined to comment directly on whether the crash was due to pilot error or air-traffic controllers but said the three captains on board had more than 10,000 flying hours of experience between them
10 1 32 The two teenage girls who died were identified Sunday as Ye Mengyuan and Wang Linjia from China's eastern Zhejiang province, according to China Central TV
10 1 33 They were among a group of 29 middle-school students and five teachers heading for a summer camp in the USA
10 1 34 Their bodies were found outside the plane, which had come to rest between runways
10 1 35 They were headed to a three-week stay in Los Angeles at a church school in the San Fernando Valley, West Valley Christian School administrator Derek Swales said
10 1 36 At least 168 people were treated for injuries
10 1 37 Eight were still in critical condition
10 1 38 After the crash, smoke billowed from the jet, and frightened passengers scampered to safety from emergency exits on the plane's fuselage
10 1 39 A massive, gaping hole blackened by fire stretched along much of the plane's top
10 1 40 It was the first fatal crash of a commercial airline in the USA since February 2009
10 1 41 The flight, which originated in Shanghai before stopping in Seoul en route to San Francisco, carried 61 U
10 1 42 S
10 1 43  citizens, 77 South Koreans and 141 Chinese
10 1 44 Early Sunday, South Korea's Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport identified the two pilots flying the jetliner at the time of the crash as Lee Jeong Min and Lee Gang Guk
10 1 45 The ministry said four pilots were on board and rotated in two-person shifts during the 10-hour flight from Seoul
10 1 46 These black boxes recovered after the crash of Asiana Airline Flight 214 in San Francisco were transported to Washington Sunday for analysis
10 1 47 (Photo:NTSB)Hersman said a component of the airport's instrument landing system that tracks the glide path of incoming airplanes was not working at the time of the crash, but other technology aids were available to the pilots on the final approach
10 1 48 The computerized system calculates a plane's path of descent and sends the information to pilots in real time
10 1 49 Vedpal Singh, who was sitting in the middle of the aircraft and survived the crash with his family, said there was no warning from the pilot or any crewmembers before the plane touched down hard and he heard a loud sound
10 1 50 "We knew something was horrible wrong," said Singh, who suffered a fractured collarbone and had his arm in a sling
10 1 51 "It's miraculous we survived
10 1 52 "Passenger Benjamin Levy, 39, said it looked to him as though the plane was flying too low and too close to the bay as it approached the runway
10 1 53 Levy, who was sitting in an emergency exit row, said he felt the pilot try to lift the jet up before it crashed and thinks the maneuver might have saved some lives
10 1 54 "Everybody was screaming
10 1 55 I was trying to usher them out," he recalled of the first seconds after the landing
10 1 56 "I said, 'Stay calm, stop screaming, help each other out, don't push
10 1 57 ' "After the initial impact, the plane's tail section was ripped off, coming to rest hundreds of feet from the main body of the aircraft, which burst into flames
10 1 58 Samsung executive David Eun, who was aboard the aircraft, was among the first to tweet photos and word of passengers
10 1 59 "Fire and rescue people all over the place
10 1 60 They're evacuating the injured
10 1 61 Haven't felt this way since 9/11
10 1 62 ''Welch reported from Los Angeles and Stanglin from McLean, Va
10 1 63 Contributing: Calum MacLeod in Beijing, Nancy Blair and Scott Martin in San Francisco, Liz Szabo, Gary Strauss, Donna Leinwand Leger, Bart Jansen, Ben Mutzabaugh, Nancy Trejos and Nancy Blair, USA TODAY; Associated Press

11 1 0 Two dead, 168 hurt in San Francisco air crashSAN FRANCISCO -- An Asiana Airlines flight from Seoul crashed on landing at San Francisco's airport Saturday, killing two passengers, injuring more than 160 and and forcing dozens of frightened passengers and crew to scamper from the heavily damaged aircraft before it was engulfed in smoke and flames
11 1 1 There were 307 on board, including 16 crew
11 1 2 Officials said 123 escaped without injury and 181 were hospitalized or treated for injuries
11 1 3 Among the injured, 49 are in serious condition and five at San Francisco General Hospital, including a child, remain in critical condition
11 1 4 Among the 47 others at San Francisco General, several were treated for minor injuries, including fractures and abrasions, and were released Saturday night
11 1 5 "It was all over in 10 seconds," says Vedpa Singh, who suffered a fractured collarbone
11 1 6 "We heard a big bang, and it was over
11 1 7 "The cause of the crash has not been determined, but the FBI has has ruled out terrorism
11 1 8 The Boeing 777 appeared to have touched down tail-first and short of the runway
11 1 9 A sheered off tail section rested several hundred feet from the main body of the aircraft, and debris from the plane littered the runway
11 1 10 Passenger Janghyung Lee told USA TODAY that the aircraft rattled wildly before landing
11 1 11 The two people who died in the crash were found outside the heavily damaged jetliner
11 1 12 Fire Chief Joanne Hayes-White said late Saturday that she did not know the ages or genders of the victims
11 1 13 FULL COVERAGE: The crash of Asiana 214SFO:  Schedules snarledSHERYL SANDBERG:  Facebook COO rescheduled flightASIANA: Flies long-distance Boeing jetsImages from the scene showed smoke billowing from the plane and emergency exits open from the plane's fuselage
11 1 14 A massive, gaping hole blackened by fire stretched along much of the plane's top
11 1 15 The flight, which originated in Shanghai China before stopping in Seoul en route to San Francisco, was carrying 61 U
11 1 16 S
11 1 17  citizens, 77 South Koreans and 141 Chinese
11 1 18 All passengers and crew were accounted for by Saturday night
11 1 19 It took several hours to account for everyone on the flight
11 1 20 "We're lucky we have this many survivors,'' said San Francisco Mayor Ed Lee
11 1 21 It was the first fatal crash of a commercial airline in the U
11 1 22 S
11 1 23  since February 2009
11 1 24 National Transportation Safety Board Chairman Deborah Hersman declined comment on whether pilot error caused the crash
11 1 25 "We have not determined what the focus of this investigation is yet,'' she said before leaving Washington, D
11 1 26 C, with a crash site-bound team of investigators 
11 1 27 "We will be looking at everything
11 1 28 Everything is on the table at this point
11 1 29 ''Hersman said the investigative team would look at all possible crash causes
11 1 30 "Obviously we have a lot of work to do,'' Hersman said before departing Washington for the crash scene
11 1 31 The investigators will work with the FAA, the aircraft's manufacturer Boeing and Korea's Air and Accident Investigation Board, Hersman said
11 1 32 Analysts in Washington, D
11 1 33 C
11 1 34 , will examine air-traffic control records, weather and aircraft maintenance issues, she said
11 1 35 Investigators on site will examine the aircraft, the cockpit data recorders and the scene
11 1 36 San Francisco International Airport was closed for several hours, with incoming flights diverted to other airports, before reopening two of four runways
11 1 37 STORY: DOT works on safety rules after previous crashesFacebook Chief Operating Officer Sheryl Sandberg said in an e-mail that she had been scheduled to take the flight, but switched to a United flight to cash in air miles for family members
11 1 38 "We are OK
11 1 39 My friend on that flight is OK, too,'' Sandberg told USA TODAY
11 1 40 Samsung executive David Eun, who was aboard the aircraft, was among the first to tweet photos and word of passengers
11 1 41 "Fire and rescue people all over the place
11 1 42 They're evacuating the injured
11 1 43 Haven't felt this way since 9/11
11 1 44 ''Asiana Airlines said on its Twitter account, "Our thoughts and prayers are with all the passengers, and flight crew on the flight
11 1 45 We hope to provide you with further info asap
11 1 46 
11 1 47 
11 1 48 We are currently investigating and will update with news as soon as possible
11 1 49 ''Boeing said in a tweet from its corporate account: "Our thoughts are with everyone affected by today's incident at SFO
11 1 50 We stand ready to assist the NTSB
11 1 51 ''Saturday's crash landing was the first fatal accident involving a major commercial carrier in the U
11 1 52 S
11 1 53  since November 2001, when a American Airlines flight to the Dominican Republic crashed on takeoff in Queens, N
11 1 54 Y
11 1 55 , killing all 260 people on board
11 1 56 The last fatal accident involving a commercial flight in the U
11 1 57 S
11 1 58  was Colgan Air Flight 3407, which crashed near Buffalo, killing 50 in 2009
11 1 59 Welch reported from Los Angeles and Swartz from San Francisco International Airport; Contributing: Donna Leinwand Leger, Bart Jansen, Ben Mautzabaugh, Elizabeth Weise, Nancy Trejos and Nancy Blair, USA TODAY; Associated Press
11 1 60

12 1 0 3rd person dies from Asiana crash, hospital says - CNN
12 1 1 comA third person -- identified only as a girl -- has died from injuries sustained in last week's crash of Asiana Airlines Flight 214, officials at the San Francisco hospital where she was being treated said Friday
12 1 2 San Francisco General spokeswoman Rachael Kagan said the "minor girl" had been in critical condition at the Bay Area hospital since last Saturday's incident
12 1 3 The hospital didn't release any information about the girl -- including her name, age or ethnicity -- who died Friday morning, according to Dr
12 1 4  Margaret Knudson, the hospital's chief of surgery
12 1 5 "It's a very, very sad day today at San Francisco General Hospital," said Dr
12 1 6  Geoffrey Manley, chief of neurosurgery
12 1 7 "We have all done everything we could
12 1 8 "Two other people -- both 16-year-old girls from China -- were reported dead soon after the Boeing 777 crash-landed at San Francisco International Airport
12 1 9 One of those teenagers was hit on the runway by a fire truck, though it's not clear whether she was already dead when she was struck, San Francisco police spokesman Albie Esparza told CNN on Friday
12 1 10 At the time, firefighters were using flame retardant that ended up surrounding areas immediately around the plane with foam, Esparza said
12 1 11 "When the truck repositioned itself to get a better aim of the fuselage, they discovered the body of the victim in the fresh track from the path of the truck," he added
12 1 12 The foam was thick enough to cover a body, Esparza noted
12 1 13 Moreover, it is difficult for those in the "industrial-size" fire trucks that responded to crash to see things on the ground, the police spokesman said
12 1 14 "Right now, we are waiting results from the coroner to determine if she died from the crash or the fire engine going over her," the police spokesman said
12 1 15 "And that will be part of our investigations, like any other case, by our hit-and-run and major accidents investigations teams
12 1 16 "Of the passengers and crew on board, 304 people survived -- 123 of whom walked away relatively unscathed and the remainder sent to hospitals
12 1 17 A handful of them remained hospitalized, including six patients at San Francisco General as of 3 p
12 1 18 m
12 1 19  (6 p
12 1 20 m
12 1 21  ET) Friday
12 1 22 That hospital's figure include two adults in critical condition with spinal cord injuries, abdominal injuries, internal bleeding, road rash and fractures
12 1 23 Besides the passengers and crew members' physical recovery, San Francisco International Airport is working to get back to normal as well
12 1 24 The airport was shut down to incoming and departing traffic for several hours after the Asiana crash, which occurred around 11:30 a
12 1 25 m
12 1 26 Saturday
12 1 27 Two of its four runways reopened later that day, though the charred remnants of the downed 777 remained -- a visible reminder of the horror that had unfolded
12 1 28 Early Friday morning, that airline's fuselage was hauled away on flatbed trucks to a remote section of the airport, said San Francisco International Airport in a press release
12 1 29 By 5:05 p
12 1 30 m
12 1 31 , a Southwest Airlines jet landed on the runway where the crash occurred -- signifying that, for the first time in six days, all four of the airport's runways were operational
12 1 32 "The tremendous efforts and around-the-clock work of airport staff, government agencies, airline tenants and contractors allowed us to complete all repairs and safety certifications for Runway 28L in a timely and efficient manner," said airport director John L
12 1 33  Martin
12 1 34 While the wreckage has been hauled away, investigators still have not pinpointed exactly why Flight 214 crashed, or who was to blame
12 1 35 An in-depth review of the cockpit voice recorder shows two pilots called for the landing to be aborted before the plane hit a seawall and crashed onto the runway, the head of the National Transportation Safety Board said Thursday
12 1 36 The first internal call by one of the three pilots in the cockpit to abort the landing came three seconds before the crash and a second was made by another pilot 1
12 1 37 5 seconds before impact, NTSB chief Deborah Hersman said
12 1 38 The agency has begun wrapping up its investigation at the airport and crews are cleaning up the debris left by the crash
12 1 39 Investigators turned the runway back over to the airport
12 1 40 The runway has been closed since Saturday's crash
12 1 41 The investigation is shifting back to NTSB headquarters in Washington, where authorities will work to find a more definitive answer about what led to the crash
12 1 42 The passenger jet's main landing gear slammed into the seawall between the airport and San Francisco Bay, spinning the aircraft 360 degrees as it broke into pieces and eventually caught fire
12 1 43 CNN's Chelsea J
12 1 44  Carter, Augie Martin and Ed Payne contributed to this report
12 1 45

13 1 0 Seconds before crash, passengers knew they were too low - CNN
13 1 1 comAre you there?Send photosAsiana Airlines Flight 214 was seconds away from landing when the passengers sensed something horribly amiss
13 1 2 The plane was approaching San Francisco International Airport under a beautifully clear sky, but it was flying low
13 1 3 Dangerously low
13 1 4 Benjamin Levy looked out the window from seat 30K and said he could see the water of the San Francisco Bay about 10 feet below
13 1 5 Even for an airport where landing strips run close to the water, the descent seemed alarming to the San Francisco man
13 1 6 "I don't see any runway, I just see water," Levy recalled
13 1 7 Further back in the Boeing 777, Xu Das had the same realization
13 1 8 "Looking through window, it looked on level of the (sea)wall along the runway," he posted on Weibo, China's equivalent of Twitter
13 1 9 Latest developments on the crashThen, with no warning from the cockpit, the plane slammed onto the edge of the runway
13 1 10 The impact severed the plane's tail and sent the rest of it spinning on its belly
13 1 11 A massive fireball and clouds of smoke shot skyward
13 1 12 First responders rushed to the scene as horrified onlookers at the airport terminal feared the worst
13 1 13 Medics found the bodies of two Chinese girls on the runway, next to the burning wreckage
13 1 14 The airline identified the girls as students Wang Linjia and Ye Mengyuan, both 16
13 1 15 Remarkably, 305 others on the plane survived the crash Saturday morning
13 1 16 A total of 70 Chinese students and teachers were headed to summer camp in the United States, China's state-run Xinhua news agency reported
13 1 17 "We're lucky there hasn't been a greater loss of life," San Francisco Fire Chief Joanne Hayes-White said
13 1 18 When rescuers arrived, they found some passengers coming out of the water
13 1 19 "There was a fire on the plane, so the assumption might be that they went near the water's edge, which is very shallow, to maybe douse themselves with water," Hayes-White said
13 1 20 Why this flight was survivableWhile 182 of them were taken to hospitals with injuries ranging from spinal fractures to bruises, another 123 managed to escape unharmed
13 1 21 Some jumped out or slid down emergency chutes with luggage in hand
13 1 22 Harrowing flightThe crash ended an otherwise mundane flight that originated in Shanghai, China
13 1 23 It made a connection in Seoul, South Korea, before flying 10 hours to San Francisco
13 1 24 Among the 291 passengers were 141 Chinese, 77 South Koreans, 61 Americans and one Japanese, Asiana Airlines said
13 1 25 The airline is one of two major airlines in South Korea; the other is Korean Air
13 1 26 At the helm of the plane was one of Asiana's veteran pilots who had been flying for 17 years, the airline said Sunday
13 1 27 Three other pilots were also on board, working in shifts
13 1 28 Once the plane fell short of the runway, passengers found themselves on a roller coaster
13 1 29 "I thought as the plane was landing, it looked like the pilot was trying to take off again," passenger Noni Singh said
13 1 30 The airplane dipped sharply
13 1 31 Expert: Flight shouldn't have been close to seawall"And then just boom, the back end just hit and flies up in the air, " Elliott Stone, another passenger, said, "and everybody's head goes up to the ceiling
13 1 32 "Dark gray smoke rose from the plane as it lay on its belly, with no landing gear evident
13 1 33 Its roof was charred and, in spots, gone
13 1 34 The back of the plane had been lopped off entirely
13 1 35 Flames and smoke burst out of its windows
13 1 36 "Honestly, I was waiting for the plane to 
13 1 37 
13 1 38 
13 1 39  start flipping upside down, in which case I think a lot of people would have not made it," Levy said
13 1 40 "If we flipped, none of us would be here to talk about it
13 1 41 "Xu and his wife were among the fortunate
13 1 42 "We quickly slung on luggage and grabbed our child and walked toward the back," Xu said on Weibo
13 1 43 "Saw the kitchen at back mostly disappeared
13 1 44 A huge hole -- very round
13 1 45 We quickly rushed out
13 1 46 Only after coming out did we see three of us had slight bruises
13 1 47 "The big questionExactly what caused the crash could take up to two years to determine, said Choi Jeong-ho, head of South Korea's Aviation Policy Bureau
13 1 48 'I just crash landed
13 1 49 I'm OK
13 1 50 Surreal'South Korean investigators will work alongside officials from the U
13 1 51 S
13 1 52  National Transportation Safety Board
13 1 53 The flight recorders from the plane have been recovered and are on the way to Washington, the NTSB said Sunday
13 1 54 The airline purchased the plane, a Boeing 777-200, in March 2006
13 1 55 Asiana CEO and President Yoon Young-doo said there was no engine failure, to his knowledge
13 1 56 "The company will conduct an accurate analysis on the cause of this accident and take strong countermeasures for safe operation in the future with the lesson learned from this accident," Yoon said
13 1 57 The survivorsMany of those who survived the crash chalked it to divine intervention
13 1 58 "I think it's miraculous that we have survived because things could have been much worse," said passenger Vedpal Singh
13 1 59 Sheryl Sandberg, Facebook's chief operating officer and author of the book "Lean In," was supposed to be on Flight 214
13 1 60 But she switched to a United flight, arriving about 20 minutes before the Asiana flight crashed
13 1 61 "Serious moment to give thanks," she wrote on her Facebook pageNot the first timePrior to Saturday's disaster, Asiana Airlines endured two deadly crashes over the past 20 years
13 1 62 In 1993, a crash near South Korea's Mokpo Airport killed 68 of the 116 people on board
13 1 63 The Boeing 737-500 went down in poor weather as the plane was attempting its third landing, the Aviation Safety Network said
13 1 64 And in 2011, a cargo plane headed from Seoul to Shanghai slammed into the East China Sea, killing the only two people on board
13 1 65 Perhaps one of the reasons so many people survived Saturday's crash was because the Boeing 777 is built so that everybody can get off the plane within 90 seconds, even if half the doors are inoperable
13 1 66 Still, many questions linger
13 1 67 Yoon, Asiana's president and CEO, told reporters he could not confirm many details of the crash, pending the investigation
13 1 68 But he started the press conference by bowing his head in apology
13 1 69 New details from cockpit voice recorderCNN's Diana Magnay, Mike Ahlers, K
13 1 70 J
13 1 71  Kwon, Kyung Lah, Amanda Watts, Jaime FlorCruz, Joe Sterling, Janet DiGiacomo, Richard Quest, Ben Brumfield, Seo Yoon-jung, Sohn Seo-hee and Dayu Zhang contributed to this report
13 1 72
