13 2 652 ['rt', 'airlin', 'identifi', 'two', '-year-old', 'girl', 'kill', 'san', 'francisco', 'crash']
14 1 0 'I just crash landed at SFO
14 1 1  I'm ok
14 1 2  Surreal' - CNN
14 1 3 comNearly three hours after the crash, David Eun walked through customs at San Francisco International Airport
14 1 4 By then, the adrenaline rush was subsiding enough that he could begin processing the enormity of it all
14 1 5 He'd just survived a catastrophe
14 1 6 The Samsung executive describes himself on his Twitter profile as being an "all-American Korean" a "pensive optimist" and a frequent flier
14 1 7 He's used to getting on planes and crossing the Pacific
14 1 8 He'd been at the same airport in April for a weeklong trip to Seoul, where Samsung is headquartered
14 1 9 Asiana Flight 214 might have been just another plane ride for Eun
14 1 10 Instead, the tech savvy businessman found himself bracing for life as something went terribly wrong in the landing
14 1 11 And he tweeted the experience
14 1 12 "I just crash landed at SFO
14 1 13  Tail ripped off
14 1 14 Most everyone seems fine
14 1 15 I'm ok
14 1 16 Surreal 
14 1 17 
14 1 18 
14 1 19 "Other passengers on the plane described a harrowing experience
14 1 20 Elliott Stone could see the tarmac below him
14 1 21 The angle of descent seemed too sharp
14 1 22 The pilot tried to raise it at the last minute, said another passenger
14 1 23 In vain
14 1 24 "And then right when it appeared to coast for the landing, all of a sudden the engine was off, like you sped up, like the pilot knew he was short
14 1 25 And then the back end just hit and flies up in the air and everybody's head goes up to the ceiling
14 1 26 "He said the back of the plane broke off
14 1 27 That's where several flight attendants were sitting
14 1 28 Several people watched the plane crash from the airport or other nearby areas
14 1 29 Still others saw it up close, sitting in other planes on the tarmac
14 1 30 For them it was like watching a frightening movie
14 1 31 Only, it was all real
14 1 32 Flight data recorders recovered from crashWitnesses describe unusual landingEverything looked normal at first
14 1 33 The plane was coming into the airport Saturday in a routine flight pattern
14 1 34 But then the wheels seemed too low too soon, said Dan Glickman
14 1 35 When a plane lands, there is typically white smoke from the friction of the wheels
14 1 36 But there was a large plume of white smoke when Flight 214 touched down
14 1 37 Then people heard a pop and a fireball burst out from underneath the aircraft
14 1 38 "It just pancaked immediately
14 1 39 It collapsed and then it slid," Glickman told CNN affiliate KTVU
14 1 40 "It just kept sliding and sliding and sliding
14 1 41 I was surprised it didn't come apart
14 1 42 It was unreal
14 1 43 "Danielle Wells also saw the plane go down
14 1 44 "Literally just witnessed a plane crash start to finish
14 1 45 I cannot stop crying I can't believe this," she said on Twitter
14 1 46 Kristina Stapchuck saw the crash from a window seat on another plane
14 1 47 She saw Flight 214 rock back and forth and the tail come off
14 1 48 Other parts came off and shattered everywhere on the runway
14 1 49 It looked like the plane was sliding on its belly all the way down the runway
14 1 50 "It all happened so suddenly," she said
14 1 51 People who watched it happen feared the worst
14 1 52 They could see the inside of the plane in orange glow from the fire
14 1 53 Smoke was billowing from the plane
14 1 54 One passenger on the plane shot a photograph that showed flames and smoke bursting out of the plane's windows
14 1 55 Those outside thought it was instant death for everyone aboard
14 1 56 Flames and smoke were bursting out of many of the aircraft's windows
14 1 57 Why the crash was survivablePassengers dashed from aircraftEunice Bird Rah's father was on Flight 214
14 1 58 He sent her text messages telling her he was fine
14 1 59 He didn't want her to worry so he chose his words carefully
14 1 60 "I think 
14 1 61 
14 1 62 
14 1 63  he didn't want me to know the full-on details of what was going on around him," Rah said
14 1 64 Passengers huddled together and pushed open emergency exit doors, Stone said
14 1 65 Some didn't bother to use evacuation slides; they jumped directly out onto the tarmac to save themselves
14 1 66 Ben Levy helped people out even though he had broken ribs
14 1 67 He tweeted a photo of fellow passengers sitting atop their bags
14 1 68 Behind them, the Asiana jet sat consumed in smoke
14 1 69 At the airport, witnesses said they could see people running out
14 1 70 "I was happy to see that some people were running out," said one man
14 1 71 "Then I went, 'Oh my god, some people lived
14 1 72 'Then emergency responders and firefighters were all over the tarmac
14 1 73 "They're evacuating the injured," Eun tweeted again
14 1 74 "Haven't felt this way since 9/11
14 1 75 "He was one of the lucky ones aboard Saturday
14 1 76 There were 291 passengers and 16 crew members on Flight 214
14 1 77 "Friends, pls don't call right now
14 1 78 I'm fine," he tweeted
14 1 79 "Most people are totally calm and trying to let the fire and rescue do their jobs," he said
14 1 80 "Just like during 9/11, most people are great and try to be helpful in crisis
14 1 81 
14 1 82 
14 1 83 "The charred carcass of the jet was still on the runway
14 1 84 Many of Eun's fellow passengers were in Bay Area hospitals
14 1 85 When he finally left customs, Eun began to think about it all -- and about all the people he cherished

15 1 0 Pilot in deadly crash had no experience landing 777 in San Francisco - CNN
15 1 1 comSan Francisco [Breaking news update at 11:33 p
15 1 2 m
15 1 3 ]The pilot of the Asiana Airlines plane that crashed in San Francisco on Saturday was making his first landing with a Boeing 777 at San Francisco International Airport, the airline said
15 1 4 But it wasn't his first time flying to San Francisco
15 1 5 The pilot, Lee Kang-gook, had flown from Seoul to the city several times between 1999 and 2004, the airline said
15 1 6 He has also clocked 43 hours flying a Boeing 777
15 1 7 [Previous story, updated at 10:14 p
15 1 8 m
15 1 9  ET]NTSB: Pilots attempted to abort landing 1
15 1 10 5 seconds before impactThe cockpit voice recorder of Asiana Airlines Flight 214 appears to show the pilots tried to abort the landing less than two seconds before the plane crashed on the runway at San Francisco International Airport, the head of the National Transportation Safety Board said Sunday
15 1 11 The plane's voice and flight data recorders show that the flight from South Korea was coming in too slow and too low and that the pilots appear to have increased speed seven seconds before impact, Deborah Hersman said
15 1 12 A stall warning sounded four seconds before the crash, and the crew then made an internal decision "to initiate a go-around 1
15 1 13 5 seconds to impact," she said
15 1 14 The NTSB's preliminary assessment of the plane's cockpit and flight data recorders appear to indicate that the flight went from a routine landing to a disaster in a matter of seconds
15 1 15 But when asked if pilot error was to blame, Hersman said the crash landing was still under investigation
15 1 16 "I would discourage anyone from drawing any conclusions at this point," she said, adding that investigators are still working to corroborate the information on the recorders
15 1 17 But what happened inside the cockpit of the Boeing 777 may well be the key factor in Saturday's accident that killed two people, injured 182 and forced the temporary closure of one of the country's largest airports
15 1 18 Amateur video obtained exclusively by CNN on Sunday shows the plane approaching the runway and striking what appears to be a seawall before spinning counterclockwise and coming to a stop
15 1 19 Fred Hayes said he shot the video about a mile from the crash scene
15 1 20 Related: Asiana Airlines crash: At a glanceSome of the answers to what happened may just hinge on what investigators found on the voice and flight data recorders
15 1 21 "What we need to do is corroborate the information we have both on the flight data recorder and the cockpit voice recorder," Hersman said
15 1 22 "
15 1 23 
15 1 24 
15 1 25 But I'll tell you some of the things we are seeing on the flight data recorder are mirroring some of the things that are going on on the cockpit voice recorder
15 1 26 "For example, she said, the increase of power in the engines appears to correlate with the cockpit crew's internal decision to do a "go-around," a call to abort the landing and try it again
15 1 27 Asiana Flight 214, with 291 passengers and 16 crew members, was at the end of a more than 10-hour direct flight from Seoul, South Korea, when it began its descent
15 1 28 According to the recorders, the flight's approach appeared normal as the 777 descended, and "there is no discussion of aircraft approach" among the crew
15 1 29 The target air speed for the approach of the flight was 137 knots, and the crew can be heard on the cockpit voice recorder acknowledging the speed, Hersman said
15 1 30 But the speed was significantly below 137 knots, and "we are not talking about a few knots," she said
15 1 31 At about four seconds before the plane crash landed, the pilots received an "aural and physical" warning inside the cockpit that the plane was on the verge of an aerodynamic stall, meaning it was about to lose its ability to stay in the air
15 1 32 The warning -- known as a "stick shaker" -- included a verbal warning the plane that was flying too low and a physical warning when the throttle shook
15 1 33 South Korean and NTSB investigators will jointly question Lee Kang-gook, the pilot who was sitting in the captain's seat of Asiana Flight 214, on Monday, Choi Jeong-ho, the head of South Korean's Aviation Policy Bureau, said
15 1 34 Lee had 43 hours of experience flying the B777-200, he said
15 1 35 They will also question Lee Jeong-min, who was sitting in the co-pilot's seat, Choi said
15 1 36 Asiana CEO and President Yoon Young-doo has said there was no engine failure, to his knowledge
15 1 37 South Korean investigators will work alongside U
15 1 38 S
15 1 39  investigators
15 1 40 The NTSB has ruled out weather as a problem and said that conditions were right for a "visual landing
15 1 41 "But investigators are looking into whether construction at the airport may have played a role
15 1 42 Construction to extend a runway safety area temporarily shut off the so-called glide slope system, which is one of several options pilots have to help them land planes safely, Hersman said
15 1 43 Internal damage to the plane is "really striking," she said, and officials are thankful there weren't more deaths
15 1 44 Survivors of the crash were being treated Sunday for injuries ranging from paralysis to "severe road rash
15 1 45 "In all, 182 people were hospitalized and 123 others walked away from the crash landing
15 1 46 The number who emerged unscathed prompted the city's fire chief to describe it as "nothing short of a miracle
15 1 47 "On the runway, medics found the bodies of the two teen girls lying next to burning wreckage
15 1 48 They were identified by Asiana Airlines as Ye Mengyuan and Wang Linjia, both Chinese nationals
15 1 49 "We were expecting a lot of burns," said Dr
15 1 50  Margaret Knudson, San Francisco General Hospital's chief of surgery
15 1 51 "But we didn't see them
15 1 52 "At San Francisco General, 17 survivors remained hospitalized, six of them in critical condition
15 1 53 Related: Passengers knew they were too lowMany of the injured said they were sitting toward the rear of the aircraft, said Knudson
15 1 54 Several suffered abdominal injuries and spine fractures, some of which include paralysis and head trauma, she said
15 1 55 Many patients also were treated for "severe road rash," which suggests "that they were dragged," Knudson said
15 1 56 The conditions of victims at other hospitals were not made public Sunday
15 1 57 Survivors and witnesses reported the 7-year-old airliner appeared to be flying too low as it approached the end of a runway near the bay
15 1 58 Expert: The plane 'should never have been close to the seawall'Airport technology called the Instrument Landing System, or ILS -- which normally would help pilots correctly approach the runway -- was not operating at the time, according to a Federal Aviation Administration bulletin
15 1 59 The ILS integrates with the aircraft's cockpit to trigger an audible warning, consultant and retired 777 pilot Mark Weiss told CNN
15 1 60  "You hear a mechanical voice that says, 'too low, too low, too low
15 1 61 '"The ILS is "nice to have," Weiss said, "but it's not critical on the 777
15 1 62 "There are redundant systems aboard the aircraft that would provide similar warnings if the plane was coming in too low, said Weiss, who has landed 777s hundreds of times
15 1 63 The pilot operating the aircraft was a veteran who had been flying for Asiana since 1996, the airline said
15 1 64 Witnesses recount the crashSurvivors reported hearing no warning from the cockpit before the landing
15 1 65 Passengers scrambled to exit a crash scene that one survivor described as "surreal
15 1 66 "When rescuers arrived, they found some passengers coming out of the water, said city fire chief Joanne Hayes-White
15 1 67 "There was a fire on the plane, so the assumption might be that they went near the water's edge, which is very shallow, to maybe douse themselves with water," she said
15 1 68 Related: Why the crash was survivableSome jumped out or slid down emergency chutes with luggage in hand
15 1 69 Statistically, 2012 was the safest year in terms of aviation accidents worldwide since 1945, according to the Aviation Safety Network
15 1 70 Data show that there were 23 fatal airliner accidents, which caused 511 deaths, according to ASN stats
15 1 71 That's well below the 10-year annual average of 34 accidents and 773 fatalities
15 1 72 Survival rates have improved due to better staff training and safety advances during the 1980s and 1990s, according to the group
15 1 73 Asiana's flight history over last 20 yearsCNN's Faith Karimi, Dana Ford, Thom Patterson and Aaron Cooper contributed to this report
15 1 74

16 1 0 Passengers begin legal action against Boeing after Asiana crash - CNN
16 1 1 comPassengers who were aboard Asiana Airlines Flight 214, which crashed in San Francisco, began legal action against Boeing Co
16 1 2 , which made the plane, according to a law firm representing passengers
16 1 3 Boeing, which is headquartered in Chicago, declined comment
16 1 4 Spokeswoman Debbie Heathers referred all calls to the National Transportation Safety Board
16 1 5 Ribbeck Law Chartered, a Chicago-based law firm, said Tuesday that it had filed the initial court petition on behalf of more than 80 passengers
16 1 6 The firm said Asiana Airlines will be added as a defendant in the next few days
16 1 7 Legal action will also be taken against several unidentified "component part manufacturers who may be responsible for this disaster," the firm said in a statement
16 1 8 Asiana spokesman Ki Won Suh declined to comment on the law firm's plans against the airline
16 1 9 The Asiana 777 fell short of its approach and crashed on the runway at San Francisco airport on July 6
16 1 10 Three people were killed and more than 180 others hurt
16 1 11 Seconds before crash, passengers knew they were too lowThe NTSB is investigating
16 1 12 The early stage of the investigation has focused heavily on actions of the crew during the landing attempt
16 1 13 The law firm filed a petition for discovery in Cook County Circuit Court in Illinois, and the petition "demands that the court orders the defendants to immediately release to the victims of the crash all relevant evidence concerning design and manufacturing records of the accident aircraft as well as any records concerning its maintenance," the law firm said in a statement
16 1 14 The 83 passengers represented by the firm include some who have serious back injuries, broken legs and brain trauma, said attorney Monica R
16 1 15  Kelly
16 1 16 During the crash, sliding ramps deployed inside the plane, blocking passengers' access to the exit door and trapping them inside the burning plane, the law firm alleged
16 1 17 Also, passengers were injured when seats collapsed during the crash-landing, Kelly said
16 1 18 The law firm also cites reports that the crash could have been caused by "a mechanical malfunction of the auto-throttle," according to the firm's statement
16 1 19 Related: Asiana to proceed with TV station suitCNN's Kyung Lah contributed to this report

17 1 0 3rd person dies from Asiana crash, hospital says - CNN
17 1 1 comA third person, identified as a minor girl, died from injuries suffered in the Asiana Airlines crash last week, hospital officials said
17 1 2 She had been in critical condition at the Bay Area hospital since the July 6 crash, San Francisco General spokeswoman Rachael Kagan saidThe hospital didn't release any additional information about her -- including her name, age or ethnicity -- in keeping with her parents' wishes
17 1 3 "It's a very, very sad day today at San Francisco General Hospital," said Dr
17 1 4  Geoffrey Manley, chief of neurosurgery
17 1 5 "We have all done everything we could
17 1 6 "Q&A: How does an air crash investigation work?Two others -- both 16-year-old girls from China -- were reported dead soon after the Boeing 777 crash-landed at San Francisco International Airport
17 1 7 One of those teenagers was hit on the runway by a fire truck, though it's unclear whether she was already dead when she was struck, San Francisco police spokesman Albie Esparza said
17 1 8 At the time, firefighters were using flame retardant that ended up surrounding areas immediately around the plane with foam, Esparza said
17 1 9 "When the truck repositioned itself to get a better aim of the fuselage, they discovered the body of the victim in the fresh track from the path of the truck," he added
17 1 10 The foam was thick enough to cover a body, Esparza noted
17 1 11 Moreover, it is difficult for those in the "industrial-size" fire trucks that responded to crash to see things on the ground, the police spokesman said
17 1 12 "Right now, we are waiting results from the coroner to determine if she died from the crash or the fire engine going over her," the police spokesman said
17 1 13 "And that will be part of our investigations, like any other case, by our hit-and-run and major accidents investigations teams
17 1 14 "Of the passengers and crew on board, 304 people survived -- 123 of whom walked away relatively unscathed
17 1 15 The others were sent to hospitals
17 1 16 Opinion: Our terror over flying has cost usA handful of them remained hospitalized, including six patients at San Francisco General
17 1 17 That hospital's figure includes two adults in critical condition with spinal cord injuries, abdominal injuries, internal bleeding, road rash and fractures
17 1 18 San Francisco International Airport is also working to get back to normal
17 1 19 The plane's fuselage was hauled away on flatbed trucks Friday to a remote section of the airport, San Francisco International Airport said in a news release
17 1 20 On Friday, a Southwest Airlines jet landed on the runway where the crash occurred -- signifying that, for the first time in six days, all four of the airport's runways were operational
17 1 21 "The tremendous efforts and around-the-clock work of airport staff, government agencies, airline tenants and contractors allowed us to complete all repairs and safety certifications for Runway 28L in a timely and efficient manner," airport director John L
17 1 22  Martin said
17 1 23 While the wreckage has been hauled away, investigators still have not pinpointed exactly why Flight 214 crashed, or who was to blame
17 1 24 Did Asiana pilot have enough 777 experience?An in-depth review of the cockpit voice recorder shows two pilots called for the landing to be aborted before the plane hit a seawall and crashed onto the runway, the head of the National Transportation Safety Board said
17 1 25 The first internal call by one of the three pilots in the cockpit to abort the landing came three seconds before the crash
17 1 26 A second call was made by another pilot 1
17 1 27 5 seconds before impact, NTSB chief Deborah Hersman said
17 1 28 The agency has begun wrapping up its investigation at the airport, and crews are cleaning up the debris left by the crash
17 1 29 Investigators turned the runway back over to the airport
17 1 30 CNN's Chelsea J
17 1 31  Carter, Augie Martin and Ed Payne contributed to this report

17 2 294 ['rd', 'person', 'die', 'asiana', 'crash']
18 1 0 NTSB: Asiana jet pilot was halfway through training to fly Boeing 777 - CNN
18 1 1 comThe pilot at the helm of Asiana Airlines Flight 214 was training to fly a Boeing 777 and was sitting next to a man in his first trip as an instructor pilot when their plane's main landing gear hit a seawall around San Francisco's airport, a U
18 1 2 S
18 1 3  official said Tuesday
18 1 4 Deborah Hersman, the head of the National Transportation Safety Board, revealed these and other details during a news conference that included information about the pilots and their flying experience, based on the interviews they've conducted with investigators
18 1 5 Having finished classroom and simulator training, the "flying pilot" -- as Hersman referred to him -- was in the piloting portion of his training to fly a Boeing 777 at the time of Saturday's crash
18 1 6 He had flown 10 legs and had about 35 hours of flying time with the 777, which put him about halfway through the training required by Asiana of 20 legs and 60 flight hours, when the plane went down, Hersman said
18 1 7 Did pilot have enough 777 experience?Sitting beside him during Saturday's flight from Seoul to San Francisco was the instructor pilot
18 1 8 The trip across the Pacific was the first time he had been an instructor pilot and the first time he'd traveled with the flying pilot, according to Hersman
18 1 9 That seemingly uneventful, more than 10-hour flight ended in a few chaotic, panicked minutes of fury, after which two people were dead and 182 others were transported to local hospitals
18 1 10 "Sections of the cabin 
18 1 11 
18 1 12 
18 1 13  are found very early in the debris field," said Hersman, who had walked a few hundred feet from the seawall where the plane's landing gear and then tail first slammed into the seawall to where it mercifully came to a rest
18 1 14 "You can see aircraft parts, gallery materials, newspapers, magazines and flooring
18 1 15 "According to the pilots' accounts, the tensions started before the plane touched ground
18 1 16 The three pilots in the cockpit -- another was in the cabin -- told investigators they set the "auto throttle" speed to 137 knots (157 mph), which is the speed it should have been going
18 1 17 Akin to cruise control, auto throttles are used to maintain a plane's speed
18 1 18 At 200 feet above ground, the instructor pilot said he noted precision approach path indicator lights indicated the giant jet was too low
18 1 19 It was then "he recognized that the auto throttles were not maintaining speed, and he established a go-around attitude," said the NTSB chief
18 1 20 "He went to push the throttles forward, but he stated that the other pilot had already (done so)
18 1 21 "Hersman cautioned anyone from jumping to conclusions as to whether a mechanical or pilot error is to blame for the crash
18 1 22 She also spoke specifically about the auto throttles, saying investigators were delving into how they were working and how they were used
18 1 23 But Hersman also stated: "The crew is required to maintain a safe aircraft 
18 1 24 
18 1 25 
18 1 26  One of the very critical things that needs to be monitored on an approach to landing is speed
18 1 27 So we need to understand what was going on in the cockpit, and also what was going on in the aircraft
18 1 28 "2 dead, 182 injured -- including 2 ejected flight attendantsWhen it departed South Korea, Flight 214 had 307 passengers and crew aboard
18 1 29 Despite the scale of the wreckage -- a hole burned through much of the cabin's roof and the aircraft's back half lopped off -- 123 walked away
18 1 30 Others weren't so lucky, most of all the two Chinese teenagers who died in the crash
18 1 31 Girls killed in crash were headed for campThose working on the flight were among the injured
18 1 32 The third pilot in the cockpit cracked a rib
18 1 33 One flight attendant was temporarily trapped by an evacuation chute that opened inside the plane
18 1 34 Two other flight attendants were not in their seats at the rear of the aircraft when the plane finally ground to a halt, because they were ejected as the aircraft broke up
18 1 35 "They were found down the runway and off to the side of the runway," Hersman said
18 1 36 Flight attendants hailed as heroesMany of those hospitalized have been released
18 1 37 At San Francisco General Hospital, for instance, 50 of the 62 patients are now free to go home
18 1 38 But others still require care
18 1 39 Four adults and one child in critical condition are still at San Francisco General suffering from internal bleeding, fractures and spinal cord, abdominal and traumatic brain injuries, according to the hospital
18 1 40 Crew recall plane being too high, then too lowThe "flying pilot" and "instructor pilot" who were in the front seat of the cockpit were not among the injured, according to Hersman
18 1 41 Asiana hired the flying pilot in 1994, after which he reported amassing nearly 10,000 hours of total flight time
18 1 42 That experience included time piloting 737, 747 and A-320 aircraft, and he was a ground school and simulator instructor for the latter model
18 1 43 The instructor pilot, a South Korean air force veteran with about 13,000 hours of flight experience, recalled Flight 214 being "slightly high when they passed 4,000 feet (and) they set vertical speed mode at about 1,500 feet per minute," explained Hersman
18 1 44 But they ended up coming in low
18 1 45 The third pilot in the cockpit told investigators that, with "the nose 
18 1 46 
18 1 47 
18 1 48  pitched up, 
18 1 49 
18 1 50 
18 1 51  he could not see the runway," said the NTSB chief
18 1 52 In the last few hundred feet before touchdown, the crew was making both lateral and vertical adjustments -- meaning they were both trying to move sideways to get toward the runway and adjust their height
18 1 53 Shock and survival: Plane crash through the eyes of childrenWhen the aircraft hit, it spun 360 degrees
18 1 54 An oil tank ruptured and leaked fuel onto the plane's right engine, starting a fire
18 1 55 Eventually, evacuation chutes deployed, and at least seven of the aircraft's eight doors were opened
18 1 56 (An eighth was found on the ground, Hersman explained
18 1 57 )Very soon after the plane stopped, tending to the wounded and the investigation began
18 1 58 That probe will continue for months, though authorities have released significant details so far
18 1 59 So much information, in fact, the Air Line Pilots Association, for a second straight day on Tuesday, criticized what it called the "NTSB's release of incomplete, out-of-context information" that "has fueled rampant speculation about the cause of the accident
18 1 60 "First responders describe eerie, chaotic moments after crashThe union further questioned whether some tools were available to the crew, claiming, for instance, that the "Instrument Landing System, a critical aid to pilots, (was) out of service
18 1 61 ""Without the full body of facts surrounding a catastrophic event, partial or incomplete information can lead to erroneous conclusions and, in turn, skew the perception of individuals' behavior," the pilots union said in its Tuesday statement
18 1 62 "This could then lead to misguided assessments of the crew's intentions and actions
18 1 63 "Hersman disputed the union's claims earlier Tuesday on CNN, saying the agency believes that transparent release of information is crucial
18 1 64 "We believe that it is always better to put out the correct information and factual information so that bad information is not able to propagate," she said
18 1 65 Aviation experts say that air crashes often involve several factors, and the San Francisco tragedy appears to be following form
18 1 66 Experience, training, crew actions, airport navigation, and now the possible role of a mechanical system are all in the mix
18 1 67 The NTSB is not expected to render a decision on probable cause for months
18 1 68 During her news conference later Tuesday, Hersman stressed that "there's still a lot of work to be done
18 1 69 ""We will not determine probable cause while we are here on scene," she said, adding there's a lot of information to collect and analyze
18 1 70 "
18 1 71 
18 1 72 
18 1 73 I would really encourage all of you to be very cautious about speculating on the cause of the crash
18 1 74 "How does an air crash investigation work?CNN's Chelsea Carter, Mike Ahlers and Michael Pearson contributed to this report
18 1 75

19 1 0 Gunman turns 'Batman' screening into real-life 'horror film' - CNN
19 1 1 comThe suspect in the mass shooting at an Aurora, Colorado, movie theater screening of the new Batman film early Friday had colored his hair red and told police he was "the Joker," according to a federal law enforcement source with detailed knowledge of the investigation
19 1 2 At least 12 people were killed in the rampage and 58 were injured, one fewer than earlier reported
19 1 3 Of those injured "nearly everyone was shot," Aurora Police Chief Dan Oates said Friday night, adding that a handful of people were hurt in the resulting chaos
19 1 4 Ten of the victims were killed inside the theater while two others died at hospitals
19 1 5 As of Friday evening, the 10 bodies had been removed from the complex and authorities were preparing to begin "the agonizing process" of notifying families, Oates said
19 1 6 A mug shot of suspect James E
19 1 7  Holmes has not been released
19 1 8 Witnesses to the shooting described him as wearing a gas mask that concealed much of his face and head
19 1 9 But the federal law enforcement source's information about the suspect's appearance fits with a statement from New York Police Commissioner Ray Kelly, who was briefed by Colorado authorities Friday
19 1 10 Oates declined to comment on Holmes' appearance other than to describe what he was wearing, and said he would not release his booking photo "for investigative reasons
19 1 11 "The Joker has long been a fixture in Batman comics and was famously brought to life by the late Heath Ledger in 2008's "The Dark Knight," the predecessor to Friday's release of "The Dark Knight Rises
19 1 12 "Ledger won a posthumous Academy Award for his sinister portrayal of the iconic villain who encourages anarchists to take over Gotham City
19 1 13 Meanwhile, authorities were faced with the difficult task of entering Holmes' Aurora apartment, which was left rigged with traps
19 1 14 "It's booby-trapped with various incendiary and chemical devices and trip wires," Oates said, adding that it could take days to work through the apartment safely
19 1 15 Five buildings around the apartment building were evacuated, Oates said
19 1 16 Residents were allowed back home briefly Friday night to retrieve such emergency items as medicine
19 1 17 Authorities have postponed until Saturday any attempts to enter the apartment and are bringing in resources from the federal government to help with the situation, Oates said
19 1 18 Shootings cast pall over 'Dark Knight Rises' blockbuster weekendPolice say Holmes, 24, dressed head-to-toe in protective tactical gear, set off two devices of some kind before spraying the Century 16 theater with bullets from an AR-15 rifle, a 12-gauge shotgun and at least one of two 
19 1 19 40-caliberhandguns police recovered at the scene
19 1 20 Oates said the guns were purchased legally by Holmes at stores in the Denver area in the past two months
19 1 21 More than 6,000 rounds of ammunition were also purchased online, according to Oates
19 1 22 A receipt obtained by CNN shows Holmes bought some of the tactical gear, including a vest and magazine pouch, online on July 2
19 1 23 Oates said investigators are "confident" that Holmes acted alone
19 1 24 The shooting unfolded inside a darkened theater packed with Batman fans, some in costume for the premiere of the movie
19 1 25 Aurora police said how the suspect entered the theater is still under investigation
19 1 26 A law enforcement source working the investigation told CNN that the gunman walked into the movie theater after purchasing a ticket
19 1 27 After the movie was under way, he went out a rear exit door, propping it open, and gathered weapons before re-entering through the door, the source said
19 1 28 As he re-entered, he tossed in a canister before starting to shoot, according to a second law enforcement source involved in the investigation and several witnesses
19 1 29 Screaming, panicked moviegoers scrambled to escape from the black-clad gunman, who shot at random as he walked up the theater's steps, witnesses said
19 1 30 It was a scene "straight out of a horror film," said Chris Ramos, who was inside the theater
19 1 31 "He was just literally shooting everyone, like hunting season," Ramos said
19 1 32 In Aurora, the agonized seek answers through faithA federal law enforcement official told CNN the man used tear gas, but Oates said Friday afternoon that it was not clear what the substance was
19 1 33 Holmes surrendered without resistance within seven minutes of the first calls from panicked moviegoers reporting the shooting, Oates said
19 1 34 Victims flooded overwhelmed hospitals
19 1 35 One of the injured is just 4 months old, the child's mother said
19 1 36 The infant was treated and released from the hospital
19 1 37 "I don't know how else to explain it
19 1 38 It's horrific," said Tracy Lauzon, director of EMS and trauma services at Aurora Medical Center
19 1 39 Theater shooting unfolds in real time on social mediaOates said the man was wearing a ballistic helmet and protective gear for his legs, throat and groin, black gloves and a gas mask
19 1 40 Jennifer Seeger, who survived the attack, said she had seen the man and thought his get-up was part of the entertainment for the film's debut
19 1 41 She said the man first shot toward the ceiling, then began shooting at people
19 1 42 He reloaded during his attack, she said
19 1 43 "He was just literally just massacring anybody that got up that was trying to run away," Seeger said
19 1 44 As of Friday afternoon, 30 people remained hospitalized, 11 of them in critical condition, according to Colorado Gov
19 1 45  John Hickenlooper
19 1 46 Holmes is scheduled to appear in an Arapahoe County, Colorado, courtroom Monday morning, Rob McCallum, spokesman for the Colorado Judicial Department, said Friday
19 1 47 The court file was sealed, according to a court order
19 1 48 He is being held in the Arapahoe County jail, Oates said
19 1 49 A statement from Holmes' family in San Diego asked for "privacy during this difficult time
19 1 50 ""Our hearts go out to those who were involved in this tragedy and to the families and friends of those involved," the statement said, adding, "We are still trying to process this information
19 1 51 "Shooting turns movie into surreal horror: 'This is real'The FBI is assisting in the investigation, officials said, though it did not appear that the incident was related to terrorism
19 1 52 Prior to Friday's shooting, Holmes' criminal record in Aurora consisted only of a traffic summons
19 1 53 Aspiring sports reporter feared dead in shootingPresident Barack Obama canceled campaign events Friday, telling supporters at what had been scheduled as a rally in Fort Myers, Florida, that "there will be other days for politics
19 1 54 ""This will be a day for prayer and reflection," he said, calling for the country to unite as one and support the victims
19 1 55 Flags at the White House were lowered to half-staff Friday afternoon in honor of the victims
19 1 56 iReporter witness: 'We have to run'A law enforcement source said two of the guns used in the attack were purchased at a Bass Pro Shop in Denver, while the two others were bought at separate Gander Mountain Guns outlets in the area
19 1 57 Investigators also found a drum magazine, capable of carrying 100 rounds of ammunition, which was attached to the AR-15 rifle, two law enforcement officials said
19 1 58 KWGN: Witnesses first thought gunfire was part of movieA statement from Bass Pro Shops said its Denver store followed appropriate protocol on the sale of the two weapons
19 1 59 Authorities also searched the suspect's car in the parking lot of the movie theater and found more magazines and ammunition, a federal law enforcement official said
19 1 60 "It was everywhere," the official said
19 1 61 Opinion: Gun control won't stop mass murderChristopher Nolan, director of "The Dark Knight Rises," condemned the shooting as "savage" and "appalling
19 1 62 ""The movie theatre is my home, and the idea that someone would violate that innocent and hopeful place in such an unbearably savage way is devastating to me," Nolan said in a statement on behalf of the cast and crew of the film
19 1 63 "Nothing any of us can say could ever adequately express our feelings for the innocent victims of this appalling crime, but our thoughts are with them and their families
19 1 64 "Four Aurora theaters showing "The Dark Knight Rises" will have extra security for the foreseeable future "out of an abundance of caution," Oates said
19 1 65 Warner Bros
19 1 66 , the studio behind the film, canceled the movie's Paris premiere, while New York police Commissioner Raymond Kelly said his officers would watch over screenings of "The Dark Knight" in the city to prevent copycat shootings
19 1 67 AMC Theatres, meanwhile, said it would not permit guests in costumes that make others uncomfortable, nor will it allow face-covering masks or fake weapons
19 1 68 911 tape: 'I need somebody to shut this movie off'Aurora, a Denver suburb, is about 13 miles from Littleton, Colorado -- site of the April 1999 Columbine High School massacre
19 1 69 In that incident, two teenage students, Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris, armed themselves with guns and bombs and shot people inside the high school
19 1 70 They killed 13 and wounded 23 before killing themselves
19 1 71 Timeline: Worst mass shootings in U
19 1 72 S
19 1 73 Are you there?Share your story on CNN iReport and post tributes to the victims
19 1 74 CNN's Carol Cratty, Ed Lavandera, Susan Candiotti, Joe Sutton, Mike Brooks, Sarah Aarthun, Joe Sterling, Tina Burnside, Chelsea Carter, Melissa Abbey and Jim Spellman contributed to this report

20 1 0 Shootings cast pall over 'Dark Knight Rises' blockbuster weekend - CNN
20 1 1 comThe early Friday release of "The Dark Knight Rises" was one of the most eagerly anticipated movie events of the summer
20 1 2 On Thursday, movie ticket seller Fandango reported that the last installment in the Christopher Nolan-directed Batman trilogy was "outpacing summer blockbuster 'The Avengers' in ticket sales at the same point in the sales cycle
20 1 3 ""The final chapter of Christopher Nolan's Batman trilogy has sold out on Fandango more than 2,000 showtimes nationwide and it's currently on track to become one of Fandango's top-selling movies of all time," the ticket seller reported
20 1 4 An attack by an armed gunman in Aurora, Colorado, at a midnight screening of "The Dark Knight Rises" was met with shock and grief throughout the country, and cast a shadow over what for fans was set to be a blockbuster weekend
20 1 5 Gunman kills 12 in Colorado movie theaterExperts said it's difficult to determine what, if any, effect the tragedy may have on either ticket sales or fan turnout in the days and weeks to come
20 1 6 "For somebody to go into a movie theater, a place of fun and escapism, and bring that kind of violence into that world is shocking and tragic," said Paul Dergarabedian, president of the box office division of Hollywood
20 1 7 com
20 1 8 "How this will affect the movie, I just don't know
20 1 9 "Shooting turns movie into surreal horrorAccording to Exhibitor Relations, the film did brisk business for its midnight screenings, raking in $30
20 1 10 6 million
20 1 11 Many fans had pre-purchased tickets for screenings across the country
20 1 12 Dergarabedian said the current focus has been rightfully on those injured and killed because of the violence
20 1 13 Beyond that it is up to Warner Bros
20 1 14 , the studio that released the film, to decide how to proceed with marketing in the wake of the tragedy, he said
20 1 15 Theater shooting unfolds in real time on social mediaWarner Bros
20 1 16 , which is owned by the parent company of CNN, has been heavily marketing the action film that includes scenes featuring lots of gunplay and violence
20 1 17 A full-page newspaper ad heralding the opening weekend contains a pull quote from Marlow Stern, assistant culture editor of Newsweek, which says, "A monumental conclusion to the epic trilogy
20 1 18 Audiences will be blown away
20 1 19 "Warner Bros
20 1 20  pulled the trailer for the film "Gangster Squad," which had been running before showings of "The Dark Knight Rises
20 1 21 "That film trailer features scenes of men armed with machine guns attacking a movie theater
20 1 22 A representative for the company told CNN that Warner Bros
20 1 23  did not plan to cancel any screenings
20 1 24 Thelma Adams, contributing editor for Yahoo Movies, said the tragedy poses a conundrum for the studio
20 1 25 "I know people at Warner Bros
20 1 26  who were called and woken up this morning who now have a huge problem on their hands," she said
20 1 27 "I think in the long run, a lot of the money is made globally with a movie like this and that will not have an impact
20 1 28 "Theater offers 'perfect killing' zone, expert saysAdams continued, "Also it's not just an opening weekend movie
20 1 29 There (are) no other movies kind of in competition this weekend as a lot of other movies stepped off this weekend and next weekend
20 1 30 Yes, there will be some impact of the revenue stream, but it's not going to really hurt
20 1 31 "Warner Bros
20 1 32  canceled the film's planned premiere in Paris on Friday and released the following statement: "Warner Bros
20 1 33  and the filmmakers are deeply saddened to learn about this shocking incident
20 1 34 We extend our sincere sympathies to the families and loved ones of the victims at this tragic time
20 1 35 "An official with Paris police told CNN there was a police presence outside the Bristol Hotel, where cast members of "The Dark Knight Rises" were staying before the premiere, to "protect all those who could be threatened
20 1 36 "Actor Gary Oldman, who portrays Commissioner Jim Gordon in the film, said in a statement, "My prayers and deepest sympathies are with the victims and their families of this horrific act
20 1 37 "Scott Beggs, managing editor of the website Film School Rejects, said the film franchise has been popular because "at the heart of (the film) is a central heroic figure that gives hope to people
20 1 38 "In Aurora, the agonized seek answersBeggs pointed out that the death of actor Heath Ledger from a toxic combination of prescription drugs in 2008 cast a bit of a pall over "The Dark Knight," but did not taint the legacy of what went on to become a critically acclaimed film
20 1 39 Ledger was posthumously awarded an Academy Award for best supporting actor for his role as The Joker in that movie
20 1 40 "(That second film) was touched by tragedy, but I believe the art ended up speaking for itself," Beggs said
20 1 41 "(The shootings in Colorado) were a tragic event that took place, which hopefully will not stop us from living our lives
20 1 42 "Are you there?Share your story on CNN iReport and post tributes to the victims
20 1 43

21 1 0 President shares story of hero who tended to friend in theater shooting - CNN
21 1 1 comSeconds after a gunman shot Allie Young in the neck in a crowded Colorado theater, a friend, Stephanie Davies, pulled her into an aisle, put pressure on her wound and dialed 911
21 1 2 Young told her friend to run, but Davies refused
21 1 3 President Barack Obama gave that account Sunday night in Aurora, praising Davies and others for heroism amid chaos and bloodshed in the shooting that killed 12 and wounded 58
21 1 4 Shooting survivors recount horrorThe women had settled in alongside others early Friday for a midnight showing of "The Dark Knight Rises," the latest installment in the Batman series
21 1 5 Suddenly a gunman threw canisters only a few feet from where the pair sat
21 1 6 Young, 19, instinctively stood to act or warn others
21 1 7 A shot ripped into her neck
21 1 8 She collapsed, blood spurting from the wound, Obama said
21 1 9 Instead of running or hiding, Davies, 21, pulled Young into the aisle and put pressure on the wound with one hand and dialed 911 with the other, Obama said
21 1 10 "I don't know how many people at any age would have the presence of mind that Stephanie did, or the courage that Allie showed," the president said
21 1 11 "They represent what's best in us, and they assure us that out of this darkness, a brighter day is going to come
21 1 12 "When the SWAT team arrived, Davies helped carry Young to an ambulance
21 1 13 Because of Davies' actions, Young is going to be fine, the president said
21 1 14 Obama flew to Aurora on Sunday evening and met with families at a local hospital for more than two hours before delivering brief remarks to the media
21 1 15 'Words are 
21 1 16 
21 1 17 
21 1 18  inadequate,' Obama tells victims' families

22 1 0 Colorado shooting: Stories of survival - CNN
22 1 1 comAurora, Colorado A few reflections from survivors of the massacre at an Aurora, Colorado, theater from CNN interviews:'That's when I felt a big ole bang in my leg'Bonnie Kate Pourciau, 18, said she is "not a huge Batman fan, really," but decided to go to the movie after she and her friend Elizabeth Sumrall stopped at a hotel in Aurora en route from Seattle to their homes in Baton Rouge, Louisiana
22 1 2 When the gunfire broke out, Pourciau told CNN affiliate KMGH from her bed in Aurora Medical Center, she thought it was special effects in the movie
22 1 3 But she soon realized what was going on
22 1 4 "That's when I grabbed Elizabeth and we ducked under our seats
22 1 5 "Crouched behind her seat, she prayed
22 1 6 "Lord, just protect us, keep us safe," she recalled thinking
22 1 7 "That's when I felt a big ole bang in my leg
22 1 8 "Once the shooting stopped, Pourciau tried to run from the theater, but didn't get far
22 1 9 "Of course, I fell because my knee is all gone," she said about the bullet wound that shattered her knee
22 1 10 "I tried to run and just stumbled and fell
22 1 11 "By now, Pourciau and her friend had separated in the panic, and another movie patron risked his life by helping her scramble to the exit, where she and Sumrall reunited, she said
22 1 12 "Elizabeth laid me on the concrete," and a police officer and a member of the National Guard soon approached
22 1 13 The officer carried her to a patrol car and the member of the National Guard wrapped her leg, which had been losing blood quickly
22 1 14 Despite the chaos, Pourciau said she felt calm
22 1 15 "I was overwhelmed with the sense of security and peace -- that it was going to be OK," she said
22 1 16 Having already undergone three surgeries on her leg, Pourciau said she expected to be transferred Thursday to a hospital closer to her home
22 1 17 'A silver lining to a very dark cloud'Baby Hugo was born Tuesday morning to Katie and Caleb Medley
22 1 18 They had gone to the movie as a treat before the expected delivery this week of their child
22 1 19 The gunfire did not strike Katie, but Caleb was shot in the face
22 1 20 He lost his right eye, suffered brain damage and is in critical condition
22 1 21 His brother said Caleb seems to understand what happened, but it was unclear whether he knew he has a baby boy
22 1 22 "He's making small improvements, baby steps every day," said Seth Medley about his eldest brother
22 1 23 When the baby was taken into Caleb's hospital room, "he moved his hand towards the baby, trying to feel his son, trying to touch him
22 1 24 "Caleb's heart rate and blood pressure rose, Seth said
22 1 25 Caleb had been doing standup comedy routines in Denver and was working full time at Target, but he had no health insurance, his brother said
22 1 26 Seth Medley said becoming an uncle was bittersweet for him
22 1 27 "We were all looking forward to this," he said
22 1 28 "It's a silver lining to a very dark cloud, but we all know Caleb, we know he's a fighter, we know he's not going to stay out of that child's life for any length of time if he can avoid it
22 1 29 "Christian Bale visits victims, families honor lost loved ones'There were kids, mothers and fathers'Josh Nowlan survived the bloodbath in Aurora, and his friends hail him as a hero for shielding them with his body
22 1 30 Nowlan was shot in the left calf and right arm in the process
22 1 31 "Of course I'm glad it's over with, and I'm glad I'm alive and I get to see my kids," Nowlan, whose sons are 7 and 9, said as his voice cracked with emotion
22 1 32 "But I also think about, you know, the other people that weren't as lucky as I was
22 1 33 There were kids, mothers and fathers that were there, and they're dead
22 1 34 I'm still alive
22 1 35 "Nowlan said he wants to go back into the screening room where the killings took place, "look down at that same seat and say 'I beat you
22 1 36 You did not take this life
22 1 37 '"Tales of heroism abound from tragedy'You don't want to leave knowing that you said something'Corbin Dates says he's not sure how he survived the killings
22 1 38 He and a friend both escaped unhurt, and he said he has "a blank feeling inside" when he looks back at the building
22 1 39 Remembering the victimsBut the experience left him sounding somewhat philosophical
22 1 40 "Certain circumstances can happen at any time," he said
22 1 41 "Try to make the most of what you can with your family, your friends, colleagues, people that you probably had bad past relationships with
22 1 42 Because you don't want to leave knowing that you said something, or didn't say enough
22 1 43 "'Who expects to be shot in a movie theater?'Christina Blache was also wounded in the early Friday massacre
22 1 44 Her friend and co-worker, Alex "Sully" Sullivan, was shot in the head, and Blache found out Saturday morning that he didn't survive
22 1 45 "He was the whole reason we all went," Blache said from her hospital bed
22 1 46 Brain condition may have helped saved shooting victimBlache served in the Air Force until four years ago, and her service included a stint in the Iraqi capital Baghdad
22 1 47 But at home, in a moviehouse, "nobody was prepared" for the violence that was unleashed, she said
22 1 48 "If you're going over to a war zone, you know there's the potential that you're going to be shot at
22 1 49 Potential that mortars are going to come over the wall
22 1 50 Potential that somebody is going to throw a grenade at you
22 1 51 Where if you're sitting in a movie theater trying to watch a movie with your friends, who expects to be shot in a movie theater?None of us did
22 1 52 "'I'm going to live my life a little bit better'Eric Hunter caught a glimpse of the killer's eyes during the rampage
22 1 53 They "looked pretty intense," but betrayed no emotion, he said
22 1 54 Like others, Hunter said he thought the first three shots were a stunt, "part of the moviegoing experience
22 1 55 "Then he heard nine more
22 1 56 He helped two teenage girls to safety as they fled the theater
22 1 57 Surviving with the guilt of livingHe says the killings have changed his life: "I'm going to be more cautious
22 1 58 I'm going to live my life a little bit better and just enjoy myself
22 1 59 "CNN's Don Lemon, Kyung Lah and Meredith Edwards contributed to this report
22 1 60

23 1 0 Tales of heroism abound from Colorado movie theater tragedy - CNN
23 1 1 comEven as a masked gunman kept firing a hailstorm of bullets in a Colorado movie theater, acts of selflessness and heroism sprouted from all across the room
23 1 2 Three of the 12 people killed died while shielding their girlfriends from the gunfire
23 1 3 And a young woman risked her life to aid her wounded friend, refusing to leave her side
23 1 4 Such valor, President Barack Obama said, represents "what's best in us" and assure the country "that out of this darkness, a brighter day is going to come
23 1 5 "Remembering the Colorado shooting victimsHere are some of the tales of bravery:Jonathan Blunk, 26Blunk, a Navy veteran, was killed trying to provide cover for his girlfriend, Jansen Young
23 1 6 "He laid up against me and had the other side of my body against the concrete seating, and I was pretty much boxed in," Young said
23 1 7 "He is a hero
23 1 8 And he was a hero before this, and before I met him
23 1 9 All he wanted to do was serve his country and help people in need," Young said
23 1 10 "He used to say he was born to serve his country, and he just really is
23 1 11 He's a true hero
23 1 12 "Blunk is survived by two young children
23 1 13 Blunk's former wife, Chantel Blunk, said their 4-year-old daughter now takes comfort in calling her father's cell phone and hearing his voice on his voice mail message
23 1 14 One victim's account: What it was like in the theaterStephanie Davies, 21, and Allie Young, 19"When the gunman initially came in and threw the (incendiary) canisters, he threw them only a few feet away from Allie and Stephanie," Obama said in a speech in Aurora on Sunday, shortly after meeting with the two friends
23 1 15 "Allie stood up, seeing that she might need to do something or at least warn the other people who were there, and she was immediately shot
23 1 16 "The bullet pierced a vein in Allie's neck, which immediately started spurting blood
23 1 17 Focusing on the victims, not the shooter"As she dropped down on the floor, Stephanie -- 21 years old -- had the presence of mind to drop down on the ground with her, pull her out of the aisle, place her fingers over where Allie had been wounded, and applied pressure the entire time, while the gunman was still shooting," the president said
23 1 18 "Allie told Stephanie she needed to run
23 1 19 "But Stephanie refused to go, and instead used her other hand to call 911
23 1 20 When police arrived, Stephanie and several others carried Allie across two parking lots to a waiting ambulance
23 1 21 Allie is expected to recover
23 1 22 "I don't know how many people, at any age, would have the presence of mind that Stephanie did, or the courage that Allie showed," Obama said
23 1 23 "And so as tragic as the circumstances of what we've seen 
23 1 24 
23 1 25 
23 1 26  are, as heartbreaking as it is for the families, it's worth us spending most of our time reflecting on young Americans like Allie and Stephanie, because they represent what's best in us, and they assure us that out of this darkness, a brighter day is going to come
23 1 27 "Victims of Colorado massacre remembered with poignant storiesMatt McQuinn, 27McQuinn died shielding his girlfriend, Samantha Yowler, during the shooting, family attorney Rob Scott said
23 1 28 Samantha Yowler was shot in the knee but is expected to make a full recovery, Scott said
23 1 29 Her brother Nick, who also was trying to protect her from the bullets, also survived
23 1 30 McQuinn and Samantha Yowler grew up in the Miami Valley region of Ohio, according to CNN affiliate WKEF
23 1 31 McQuinn's stepfather, David Jackson, told CNN affiliate WHIO that the young couple was planning to move back to Springfield, Ohio
23 1 32 "I know he's a hero," Jackson said
23 1 33 "He and Sam were very much in love and planning their life together
23 1 34 I am sure they were thinking very seriously of getting married soon
23 1 35 "'Words are
23 1 36 
23 1 37 
23 1 38  inadequate,' Obama tells families of Colorado shooting victimsAlex Teves, 24Teves was killed while protecting his girlfriend, Amanda Lindgren
23 1 39 "I wouldn't be here without him," Lindgren said
23 1 40 Teves graduated in June with a master's degree in counseling psychology from the University of Denver, where he met Lindgren
23 1 41 His best friend, Ryan Cooper, recalled Teves' kindness
23 1 42 "We love going to football and basketball games together," Cooper said
23 1 43 "As much as he loved that, he would take time and miss those games to mentor kids in the community who didn't have dads and were just really hurting
23 1 44 "Share your tribute to the victims on CNN iReport
23 1 45 CNN's Anderson Cooper contributed to this report
23 1 46

24 1 0 Colorado hospitals chip in for shooting victims' care - CNN
24 1 1 comWith many patients still being cared for after last week's Colorado movie theater shootings, one burden is being lifted by some of the hospitals: medical expenses
24 1 2 Children's Hospital Colorado said it will use its charity care program and donations to cover medical expenses for victims of the shooting who do not have insurance
24 1 3 Victims who do have insurance will have their co-pays and deductible-related expenses waived
24 1 4 "We are committed to supporting these families as they heal," Elizabeth Whitehead, spokeswoman for Children's Hospital Colorado, said in a statement
24 1 5 HealthONE, the health-care system that includes the Medical Center of Aurora and Swedish Medical Center, which both are treating patients from the theater shooting, is also taking measures to alleviate victims' costs
24 1 6 Father campaigns for more time off for grieving parentsThe health system will "eliminate personal financial responsibility for hospital charges as appropriate to each patient and the circumstances these individuals find themselves in" with regard to the shooting victims, according to a statement
24 1 7 Denver Health issued a statement saying that the hospital discounts bills for all patients unable to pay for co-pays and deductibles by 70%, following Colorado state law
24 1 8 Each case is evaluated individually
24 1 9 Almost half of all of the hospital's patients are uninsured
24 1 10 There are more than 1
24 1 11 5 million people in Colorado who were uninsured or underinsured as of November, according to the Colorado Health Access Survey
24 1 12 This represents nearly 30% of people who live in the state
24 1 13 Underinsured means people have significant out-of-pocket medical costs despite carrying insurance
24 1 14 The most-often reported reason for not having health insurance is high cost, the survey found
24 1 15 Not having access to insurance sponsored by employers, and the loss or transition of jobs, were also frequently mentioned
24 1 16 Fewer employers are now providing health insurance, given that the percentage of Coloradans who got insurance through work was 58%, down from 64% in 2008-09
24 1 17 Those between 19 and 34 years old are the population group most likely to be uninsured in the state, with 28% of them lacking insurance, according to the survey
24 1 18 Many victims of the Colorado theater shooting are in this age range
24 1 19 Brain condition helps save victimSome find themselves uninsured because they don't have coverage through work, but others make the conscious decision to not buy insurance because they don't have any major illnesses or medical needs, said Dr
24 1 20  Ned Calonge, president and CEO of the Colorado Trust, which administers the health survey every other year
24 1 21 "There is a bit of a gamble in saying, 'I'm young and healthy,' " Calonge said
24 1 22 "The reality is, you're just one bad day away from a major hospitalization
24 1 23 "Hospitals respond to Colorado shootingLegally, hospitals cannot turn uninsured patients away in emergency situations, so it's not surprising that this would apply for Colorado shooting victims, Calonge said
24 1 24 But extending additional resources for victims, including those who do have insurance, is philanthropic
24 1 25 It will be more of a challenge for hospitals financially if they decide to cover follow-up care for shooting victims, since they're not bound by law to do so and there's no obvious source of money for it, he said
24 1 26 "I'm proud of the medical community
24 1 27 I'm proud of our larger community with our response, how quickly we stepped up to the plate, in view of this senseless tragedy," he said
24 1 28 He praised hospitals for making sure patients could be treated "without worrying about who's going to pay for it
24 1 29 "How to help the victims

25 1 0 Look to the good in humankind -- look to heroes, says grieving father - CNN
25 1 1 comPhoenix Alex Teves treasured Marvel and DC comics with their Spider-Man and Batman icons, and he was at his best in high school when he wrote about the superhero genre in English class
25 1 2 He revered the enduring themes of good versus evil, and he is remembered here, in the place where he grew into a man, as one of the good guys: a boy who inspired an "Alex Teves Day" at school, pursued a calling to heal both minds and bodies, and died at age 24 facing evil in the darkness of a crowded Colorado movie theater
25 1 3 "If you want to describe Alex in one word, he was just good," says his father, Tom Teves
25 1 4 "He wasn't a standout in anything, but he cared about people
25 1 5 "It is the goodness of humanity that Teves wants the world to know and remember: the virtues of his son -- and the 11 others killed at a midnight premiere of the latest Batman movie, "The Dark Knight Rises," in a cinema in Aurora, Colorado
25 1 6 That desire has taken shape as a crusade
25 1 7 In the midst of mourning his first born, Tom Teves has wrested purpose from his grief -- the Alex Teves Challenge, he calls it
25 1 8 He demands that the media stop naming and showing images of the gunmen in mass murders
25 1 9 Publicity glorifies killers, he says, and the notoriety spurs others to commit the same barbarities just for attention
25 1 10 Columbine
25 1 11 Virginia Tech
25 1 12 Tucson
25 1 13 And now Aurora
25 1 14 Alex Teves had just completed his master's degree in psychological counseling
25 1 15 His father says he would have condemned the practice of focusing on the murderers
25 1 16 Remember the victims, the heroic acts, Tom Teves exhorts
25 1 17 Let good triumph over evil
25 1 18 'A zest for life'Alex Teves died shielding his girlfriend from the rain of bullets
25 1 19 His last act was more than just heroism
25 1 20 It attested to his nature to help humankind
25 1 21 Opinion: They lost their lives, upheld the codeFresh out of the University of Denver with his master's degree, he was readying to seek another degree, a bachelor's in physical therapy at the University of Colorado at Boulder
25 1 22 He chose this long path because he wanted to heal the whole person, his family says
25 1 23 Tom Teves is deeply satisfied that the oldest of the couple's three children, all sons, came to know himself so well
25 1 24 "He told me one day, 'I'm not going to do what you do -- because it's business,'" says Teves, an executive for a corporate services firm
25 1 25 Alex said he didn't have it in him to order people around
25 1 26 "And it was my proudest moment
25 1 27 He knew what he wanted to do," the father adds
25 1 28 Alex's mother, Caren, recalls his ever-present smile and appetite for life
25 1 29 "He loved food
25 1 30 He loved to travel
25 1 31 He loved to explore new things
25 1 32 He just had a zest for life
25 1 33 He just wanted to experience everything he could
25 1 34 "I'm glad he did as much as he could in the time he had here
25 1 35 "He met his girlfriend in graduate school, and Alex planned to marry her once he finished his studies, the mother says
25 1 36 Tales of heroism in AuroraIn the elegantly designed Phoenix community of Ahwatukee, where the boulevards are desert-landscaped with saguaro cacti and palo verde trees, Alex was such an ordinary guy of irrepressible cheer that he was celebrated for it by his classmates at Desert Vista High School, a high-performing public school opened in 1996 that sends graduates to the Ivy League
25 1 37 Every day, he wore a crisp, white T-shirt, blue jeans and loafers to school; he just wasn't into materialism and liked to think of the more important things, his mother said
25 1 38 By his senior year, his AP statistics classmates -- and then the entire class of 2006 -- decided to hold a day in his honor
25 1 39 Everyone came to school dressed like him
25 1 40 And now, says his mother, friends and supporters of those slain in the movie theater massacre held a memorial service in Denver with an Alex Teves dress code, and friends in Hawaii told the family they were planning a similarly attired service
25 1 41 Alex Teves was a cooperative student with a streak for being fun and funny, says high school math instructor Francoise Dastous, who teaches the statistics class
25 1 42 "He really didn't have a clique per se
25 1 43 He got along well with everybody, and everybody wanted to be friends with him
25 1 44 "Alex once recounted to the class a hiking adventure that went awry, Dastous says
25 1 45 For anyone else, the experience would have been horrific, "but Alex put a positive spin on it," Dastous says
25 1 46 "He was just really engaging and really fun to listen to
25 1 47 "Six years have passed since the 57-year-old teacher had Alex in class, but the memories are clear
25 1 48 "He just really kind of stood out from the other kids
25 1 49 He was always smiling
25 1 50 "Alex was an honors student whom other faculty recalled as having a sense of humor, says Anna Battle, principal of the 3,000-student school, one of the largest in Arizona
25 1 51 "He wasn't Mr
25 1 52  Flamboyant
25 1 53 He wasn't Mr
25 1 54  Social Anybody
25 1 55 He was an even-keeled, pleasant, quality young man who loved superheroes," Battle says
25 1 56 "One English teacher said he was a good writer and wrote exceptionally about superheroes
25 1 57 "Unfortunately, it sounds like the young man who created this incident (in the Colorado movie theater) had some challenges that Alex may have been able to help," Battle adds
25 1 58 The alleged gunman is also 24 and was a neuroscience doctoral student at University of Colorado Anschutz Medical Campus in Aurora
25 1 59 According to a court document filed by his public defense attorneys, he was also a patient of a university psychiatrist
25 1 60 'My hero every day'Alex Teves will not be forgotten
25 1 61 His father shares one more memory
25 1 62 Alex was injured with a group of kids when their car rolled over in an accident in the desert
25 1 63 He was a student at the University of Arizona at the time
25 1 64 When an ambulance arrived, Alex insisted the other passengers get inside first, his father recalls, even though he needed immediate treatment, too
25 1 65 Once in intensive care, Alex asked his father to visit one of his friends who was hospitalized because that boy's parents had yet to arrive
25 1 66 "That's the kind of kid he was," the father says
25 1 67 "The world is worse off because he's not in it
25 1 68 "4 Colorado shooting victims remembered for vitality, selflessnessThat the suspect had dyed his hair red to resemble the villain Joker of the Batman series is a cruel turn of fate that enrages the grieving father
25 1 69 Tom Teves doesn't want his son's legacy to be defined by a gunman
25 1 70 When the man first appeared in court last week in Colorado, Teves was there
25 1 71 He calls the suspect "a coward
25 1 72 ""He didn't look like much," Teves says
25 1 73 "My son could have wiped the floor with him
25 1 74 "Then the father continues: "If he would have known my son, he would have helped him
25 1 75 "He returns to his challenge to the media
25 1 76 He blames news outlets, including CNN, for playing a role in perpetuating mass shootings
25 1 77 "You make him out to be a madman," he says of the man suspected of killing his son
25 1 78 "He knew he was going to be on television
25 1 79 These guys are playing you like fiddles
25 1 80 Either you're not that bright -- I used a better word than I was thinking of -- or you don't care and you're using it to sell advertising, and then you're the worst thing on the face of the earth
25 1 81 "Tom and Caren Teves have been married 28 years
25 1 82 He worked two or three jobs sometimes, so that their kids could benefit from having their mother at home full-time
25 1 83 Now the couple faces raising their 16- and 17-year-old sons without their big brother
25 1 84 "He was my hero every day," Teves says
25 1 85 The father isn't surprised by the way Alex responded when savagery slipped inside the movie theater
25 1 86 "Alex is in heaven," he adds
25 1 87 "I'm quite sure of it
25 1 88 "His anger subsides
25 1 89 The couple is accompanied by Caren Teves' sister and her husband, whom the Teveses earlier picked up at the Phoenix airport
25 1 90 The in-laws, Joe and Carla Morgan, express outrage that the suspect's photo appears five times on the front page of a national newspaper, overwhelming any photos of Alex and the others who lost their lives
25 1 91 "Stop showing cowards and start showing heroes," Tom Teves says, "so that another father doesn't feel the hole in his body that I have and I know will never go away
25 1 92 "He puts his hand over his heart
25 1 93 His wife extends her hand and joins his
25 1 94 "It's got to end," he says
25 1 95 "You do your part, and I promise to do the other
25 1 96 "He says he will spend his days reminding the media of this challenge in his son's name
25 1 97 Remembering Rebecca Wingo, Aurora victimHow to help the victims of the Colorado massacreDriven by personal tragedy, man builds crosses for Aurora victims, thousands of others

26 1 0 Looking into the minds of killers - CNN
26 1 1 comEditor's note: Jeffrey Swanson is a professor in psychiatry and behavioral sciences at Duke University's School of Medicine
26 1 2 A witness to the horrific shooting rampage in the Colorado movie theater called it "the longest minute" of his life
26 1 3 One can only imagine
26 1 4 But the second longest minute may be the waiting for someone -- the authorities, the pundits, the doctors -- to tell us "why" these killings happened
26 1 5 Police say James Holmes, a 24-year-old graduate student in a neurosciences program, called himself the Joker and rained merciless bullets on strangers watching a Batman movie
26 1 6 Why?Colorado theater shooting suspect makes first court appearanceAlready, the speculations are flooding in
26 1 7 There's a celebrity psychiatrist saying it was a "failure of empathy" likely rooted in the shooter's early life psychological pain
26 1 8 What about asking the accused shooter's parents?"Listen, these folks that are now flying to join their son in Colorado, if you were to ask them, 'What three things are you most sensitive about not telling people, about your family or your son's personal development, or the things that are most painful to relate' -- there's your answer
26 1 9 "Another psychiatrist thinks that people who commit crimes like this are "unfailingly unable to form satisfying sexual attachments, and their masculinity essentially gets replaced with their fascination for destruction
26 1 10 "Big Religion has also weighed in
26 1 11 "The product of pure evil 
26 1 12 
26 1 13 
26 1 14  a depraved individual taking his free will to the extreme," says the president of Focus on the Family
26 1 15 The head of the Southern Baptists commented that the incident "tells the truth about unbridled human sin
26 1 16 "They should all shut up
26 1 17 Let the police work
26 1 18 Let a competent clinician conduct a private evaluation
26 1 19 Let the professional reporters find out what really happened
26 1 20 Former colleague shocked that Holmes is theater shooting suspectOn the face of it, a deliberate rampage to kill strangers is the act of a deviant consciousness of some kind
26 1 21 But we don't know whether the accused killer's mind may have been driven by acute symptoms of a psychiatric disorder that impairs thought and perception of reality, by a personality misshaped through a troubled past, or by something else entirely
26 1 22 We simply don't know
26 1 23 What we do know, based on the best available scientific evidence on the link between violence and mental illness in populations, is that most violence is not caused by a major psychiatric condition like schizophrenia, bipolar disorder or depression
26 1 24 Psychiatric disorder accounts for only about 4% of violent behavior, across the spectrum from minor to serious assaultive acts
26 1 25 And the vast majority of people with serious mental illnesses do not behave violently
26 1 26 If research on patterns of violence in populations tells us anything, it's that no single thing causes assaultive behavior
26 1 27 Even when serious psychopathology plays a role, it is almost never a sufficient explanation
26 1 28 Other variables -- personal background characteristics and life experience, features of the social environment, substance abuse -- all may interact to make violent acts statistically more likely
26 1 29 That makes it complicated to explain and very difficult to predict actions on an individual level
26 1 30 Court appearance fuels theories about Colorado shooting suspectAfter the fact, rare and appalling acts of violence somehow look predictable, and thus, preventable
26 1 31 It is natural to turn to the experts, but they always come up short
26 1 32 They are notoriously bad at forecasting even garden variety violence, to say nothing of finding the one-in-a-million would-be mass shooter
26 1 33 When we total up the contributions of all the risk factors with known links to violent behavior, most of it is left unexplained
26 1 34 When we describe the common characteristics of mass shooters, we're left with a profile that fits tens of thousands of troubled young men who would never actually do such a senseless thing
26 1 35 Is Holmes a psychopath?The true "reasons" that motivated the terrible act of which he is accused may always remain obscure
26 1 36 But what should not be obscure is how easy it is for troubled young men legally to acquire a small arsenal of firearms in the United States
26 1 37 If Holmes hadn't been able to get his hands on the guns police say he used, this would be a different story 
26 1 38 Opinion: Mass murder and powerful firearmsPeople can disagree about whether 270 million firearms in private hands in the country is too many guns
26 1 39 But they should not disagree that 300,000 people dying from gunshots in the past decade is too many wasted lives
26 1 40 The notion of forbidding assault weapons and large-capacity ammunition magazines -- machines specifically designed to kill multiple people in the twinkling of an eye -- is not about infringing the Second Amendment
26 1 41 It is about common sense and protecting the public
26 1 42 Such weapons were successfully legally banned in the United States from 1994 to 2004; they should be banned again
26 1 43 Still, dangerous guns per se are not the only problem, and banning them is only part of the solution
26 1 44 We also need better means of identifying dangerous people who should not have access to guns
26 1 45 Research shows that one of the highest risk times for violence in people who develop a psychotic illness is their first episode -- the period right before they establish any record with the formal mental health care system
26 1 46 Gun laws such as the federal Brady Act that are implemented through background record searches won't find these individuals
26 1 47 But even having a formal record of involuntary psychiatric hospitalization is no guarantee that the relevant information will be available at the point of purchase of a firearm
26 1 48 Opinion: When will America wake up to gun violence?In Colorado, only a tiny fraction (about 1%) of people who have gun-disqualifying mental health histories have been reported to the National Instant Check System, where they could be discovered in a routine background check of a prospective gun purchaser
26 1 49 A felony conviction is also supposed to disqualify people from buying a gun, but only 40% of murder suspects have such a previous record of conviction
26 1 50 The present national moment of grief and soul searching should not become another occasion for oversimplifying the problem of gun violence and laying the blame on any one thing -- "it's the guns" or "it's untreated mental illness" or "it's the information system" or "it's the violent popular culture in society
26 1 51 "It may be all of those things
26 1 52 We need to address all of the variables and come up with smart evidence-based policies
26 1 53 Looking inside the killer's head should not be the first place to start
26 1 54 Follow us on Twitter @CNNOpinionJoin us on Facebook/CNNOpinionThe opinions expressed in this commentary are solely those of Jeffrey Swanson
26 1 55
