27 1 0 Victims of Colorado massacre remembered with poignant stories - CNN
27 1 1 comAurora, Colorado Stories of heroism, zest for life, a birthday celebration that turned tragic have unfolded as family and friends recall loved ones killed in Friday's mass shooting at a Colorado movie theater
27 1 2 Also emerging was the story of Hugo, who was born Tuesday
27 1 3 Almost all of the 12 victims were young -- including a 6-year-old girl who had just learned to swim
27 1 4 The cause of death in all cases is related to gunshot wounds, according to the Arapahoe County Coroner's Office
27 1 5 Remembering the victims through photos, memoriesJonathan T
27 1 6  Blunk, 26Blunk served for five years in the U
27 1 7 S
27 1 8  Navy
27 1 9 He had been planning to fly Saturday to Reno, Nevada, to see his wife, Chantel, his 4-year-old daughter and his 2-year-old son
27 1 10 "We were going to have a family day," Chantel Blunk said
27 1 11 Instead, she put away the dress her daughter had picked out to wear to the airport
27 1 12 "I tried to tell her we wouldn't see Daddy anymore, but that he would still love us and look over us
27 1 13 "The couple married in 2007 and separated in 2010, she said
27 1 14 They remained on good terms after Jonathan moved to Colorado
27 1 15 Blunk died shielding his girlfriend from the gunfire inside the theater
27 1 16 Chantel Blunk said she wants her husband to have a military funeral
27 1 17 She said she will remember Jonathan's humor, spontaneity and attention to family
27 1 18 "We love him and he is going to be remembered as a hero," she said
27 1 19 Video: Blunk was a heroAlexander J
27 1 20  Boik, 18A Facebook page was created in memory of Boik, a Gateway High School student who was at the theater with his girlfriend and a friend
27 1 21 "AJ was an awesome kid and a truly Inspirational teammate," one Facebook entry said
27 1 22 "You cant find someone with a brighter smile and more positive outlook on life
27 1 23 There to help you up when your down and One to carry on life with such an intelligence
27 1 24 "Boik was an independent distributor for Organo Gold, a coffee company, and lived in Aurora, according to what appears to be his personal Facebook page
27 1 25 James Crofter, father of Jordan Crofter, Boik's friend who survived the shooting, said Jordan and Boik played lacrosse together
27 1 26 Boik's girlfriend also was in the theater
27 1 27 She and Jordan found each other outside the theater, but Boik did not make it out
27 1 28 One victim's account: What happened inside the theaterAir Force Staff Sgt
27 1 29 Jesse E
27 1 30  Childress, 29Childress, an Air Force reservist, was a cybersystems operator on active duty with the 310th Force Support Squadron at Buckley Air Force Base in Colorado
27 1 31 He was from Thornton, Colorado
27 1 32 "Jesse was an invaluable part of the 310th family," said Lt
27 1 33  Col
27 1 34  Pat Walsh, who was Childress' supervisor, according to The Washington Post
27 1 35 "He literally touched everyone in the wing -- over 1,000 people
27 1 36 "Three of Childress' Air Force colleagues traveled from Buckley to honor him at a memorial near the theater, The Denver Post reported
27 1 37 "He was a huge part of our unit, and this is a terrible loss
27 1 38 The person that did this was an incredible coward," said Air Force Chief Master Sergeant Schwald, according to the Denver newspaper
27 1 39 She declined to give her first name
27 1 40 Gordon W
27 1 41  Cowden, 51Cowden took his two teenage children to the theater
27 1 42 His children escaped unharmed, according to California's Ventura County Star
27 1 43 A family spokesman described Cowden as a "loving father, outdoorsman and small-business owner," according to the Star
27 1 44 "Cowden was a true Texas gentleman that loved life and his family
27 1 45 A quick-witted world traveler with a keen sense of humor, he will be remembered for his devotion to his children and for always trying his best to do the right thing, no matter the obstacle
27 1 46 "Focusing on the victims, not the shooterJessica Ghawi, 24Aspiring sports reporter Ghawi narrowly avoided a shooting in Toronto just last month -- an incident that prompted her to reflect on life on her blog
27 1 47 The Toronto shooting at the Eaton Centre left one person dead and seven wounded
27 1 48 "I was shown how fragile life was on Saturday
27 1 49 I saw the terror on bystanders' faces
27 1 50 I saw the victims of a senseless crime
27 1 51 I saw lives change," she wrote at the time
27 1 52 "I was reminded that we don't know when or where our time on Earth will end
27 1 53 When or where we will breathe our last breath
27 1 54 "Ghawi, who also went by the name Jessica Redfield, grew up in Texas and interned at Ticket 760, a sports radio station in San Antonio, before moving to Denver to try to break into the television market there
27 1 55 A memorial service is scheduled for July 28 in San Antonio
27 1 56 Brother: Ghawi an aspiring sports writerPetty Officer 3rd Class John Thomas Larimer, 27Like his father and grandfather, Larimer chose to join the U
27 1 57 S
27 1 58  Navy
27 1 59 He was serving at his first post, said his father, Scott Larimer
27 1 60 A Navy notification team officially informed the family in Crystal Lake, Illinois, around midnight Saturday, a statement from the family said
27 1 61 "He was an outstanding shipmate, a valued member of our Navy team and an extremely dedicated sailor," said Cmdr
27 1 62 Jeffrey Jakuboski
27 1 63 "Sailors were really drawn to his calming demeanor and exceptional work ethic
27 1 64 He was also known as that quiet, extremely competent professional
27 1 65 ""He was doing extraordinarily well" and had a bright future ahead of him, Jakuboski said
27 1 66 His unit, part of U
27 1 67 S
27 1 68  Fleet Cyber Command/U
27 1 69 S
27 1 70  10th Fleet, was stationed at Buckley AFB
27 1 71 Larimer had been in the service for about one year
27 1 72 He had not seen combat
27 1 73 "We send our thoughts and prayers out to the families of the other victims and those still recovering in the hospital," his family said
27 1 74 "We love you, John, and we will miss you always
27 1 75 "Tales of heroism abound from tragedyMatthew R
27 1 76  McQuinn, 27McQuinn died trying to provide cover for his girlfriend, Samantha Yowler, during the shooting, according to family attorney Rob Scott
27 1 77 Yowler and her brother Nick, who also was trying to protect her from the bullets, both survived
27 1 78 Samantha Yowler, wounded in the knee, is expected to make a full recovery, Scott said
27 1 79 Nick was unharmed
27 1 80 McQuinn and Samantha Yowler grew up in the Miami Valley region of Ohio, according to CNN affiliate WKEF
27 1 81 The two had been dating for a couple of years
27 1 82 McQuinn graduated from Vandalia-Butler High School in 2004
27 1 83 The couple met at a Springfield, Ohio, Target store and moved last November to Denver, the Dayton Daily News reported
27 1 84 The victim's stepfather, David Jackson, told CNN Dayton affiliate WHIO that the couple was planning to move back to Springfield soon
27 1 85 "I know he's a hero," said Jackson
27 1 86 "He and Sam were very much in love and planning their life together
27 1 87 I am sure they were thinking very seriously of getting married soon
27 1 88 "iReport: McQuinn seized the dayMicayla C
27 1 89  Medek, 23Medek, known to her friends as Cayla, was "very spiritual and close to God," cousin Anita Busch told CNN
27 1 90 Her family is tightly knit, Busch said
27 1 91 Medek's Facebook page describes her as a "sandwich artist/closer" at Subway in Aurora, and a student of general studies at the Community College of Aurora with plans to graduate in 2015
27 1 92 She lived in Westminster, Colorado, but was from Aurora, Busch said
27 1 93 "I'm a simple independent girl who's just trying to get her life together while still having fun," Medek wrote on her Facebook page
27 1 94 Busch said the family did not learn of Medek's death for 19 hours
27 1 95 "We had been desperately trying to find her," she said
27 1 96 Veronica Moser-Sullivan, 6Thirteen-year-old Kaylan was Veronica's babysitter, and she was seated with the girl and Veronica's mother when the shooting began
27 1 97 "He just kept firing and then he would stop like he was reloading and he kept firing at anyone he saw," Kaylan told CNN's Poppy Harlow
27 1 98 Kaylan watched as three people with her were shot -- Veronica, the girl's mother, Ashley Moser, and their pastor, Michael Walker
27 1 99 "I felt like it was partly my job to protect her and even if I wasn't her babysitter I would still feel that same because she was just a child," she said
27 1 100 Lying on the theater floor, she called 911, then put her hand on Veronica's ribcage to see if she was breathing
27 1 101 "But she wasn't breathing so I started freaking out and then they told me to do CPR and I told them I couldn't because her mother was on top of her and couldn't move
27 1 102 "Described as a "vibrant little girl," Veronica -- an only child -- had just learned to swim and was "excited about life," her great-aunt said
27 1 103 The girl's 25-year-old mother was critically injured, with wounds to the neck and abdomen, said Moser's niece, Annie Dalton
27 1 104 "Her whole life has changed in a flash, for what?"Moser had just been accepted into a licensed practical nurse program, Dalton told reporters
27 1 105 "Obviously, with this injury she is not going to be able to start school like she planned
27 1 106 "More on the victimsAlex M
27 1 107  Sullivan, 27Alex "Sully" Sullivan went to the movie to celebrate his birthday, two days before the first anniversary of his marriage to Cassie
27 1 108 "Oh man one hour till the movie and its going to be the best BIRTHDAY ever," he tweeted
27 1 109 "The Sullivan family lost a cherished member of their family," a representative said in a statement
27 1 110 "Alex was smart, funny, and above all loved dearly by his friends and family
27 1 111 "His uncle, Jim Loewenguth, said Sullivan was "full of joy" and "never had a bad chip on his shoulder
27 1 112 "Alexander C
27 1 113  Teves, 24Alexander Teves recently graduated from the University of Denver with a master's degree in counseling psychology
27 1 114 "The university extends its deepest condolences to his family and friends, including the many current students and faculty who knew and worked with Alex," the school said in a statement
27 1 115 Teves died protecting his girlfriend, Amanda Lindgren
27 1 116 "I wouldn't be here without him," Lindgren told CNN Monday
27 1 117 His aunt, Barbara Slivinske, said Alex was living in Colorado and had just completed graduate school there in June
27 1 118 His parents were in Colorado, retrieving his body, according to Slivinske, who added, "He was a wonderful nephew
27 1 119 "Rebecca Ann Wingo, 32Rebecca Wingo was originally from Quinlan, Texas, and lived in Aurora, Colorado
27 1 120 Her father, Steve Hernandez, announced his daughter's death on Facebook, saying, "I lost my daughter yesterday to a mad man, my grief right now is inconsolable
27 1 121 ""I hear she died instantly, without pain, however the pain is unbearable
27 1 122 Lord why, why, why????" Hernandez wrote
27 1 123 "I sit here and resist this entry however I feel I must, in disgust, in dismay, in prayer, I love you my daughter Rebecca, we all will miss you
27 1 124 "Wingo joined the Air Force after high school, became fluent in Mandarin and served as a translator, according to CNN Dallas-Fort Worth affiliate WFAA
27 1 125 She had "the sweetest smile you've ever seen," said friend Hal Wallace
27 1 126 "She got prettier as she grew older
27 1 127 "Wingo moved to Colorado with her two young girls, and wrote about how the younger one was excited about starting kindergarten
27 1 128 Said Wallace: "In the blink of an eye something happens and completely changes everyone's life -- forever
27 1 129 "Hugo Medley, infant survivorAmid the tales of strength in the face of death, a tale of survival has emerged
27 1 130 Baby Hugo was born Tuesday morning to Katie and Caleb Medley
27 1 131 They had gone to the movie as a treat before the expected delivery this week of their child
27 1 132 The gunfire did not strike Katie, but Caleb was shot in the face, lost his right eye, suffered brain damage and is in critical condition
27 1 133 His brother said Caleb seems to understand what happened, but it was unclear whether he knew he has a baby boy
27 1 134 "He's making small improvements, baby steps every day," said Seth Medley about his eldest brother
27 1 135 When the baby was taken into Caleb's hospital room, "he moved his hand towards the baby, trying to feel his son, trying to touch him
27 1 136 "Caleb's heart rate and blood pressure rose, Seth said
27 1 137 Caleb had been doing standup comedy routines in Denver and was working full time at Target, but he had no health insurance, his brother said
27 1 138 Seth Medley said becoming an uncle was bittersweet for him
27 1 139 "We were all looking forward to this," he said
27 1 140 "It's a silver lining to a very dark cloud, but we all know Caleb, we know he's a fighter, we know he's not going to stay out of that child's life for any length of time if he can avoid it
27 1 141 "Did you know the victims?Share your photos and memories with CNN iReportCNN's Nick Valencia, Barbara Starr, Holly Yan, Carma Hassan, David Ariosto, Phil Gast, Greg Morrison and Allison Rampley contributed to this report
27 1 142

28 1 0 4 Colorado shooting victims remembered for vitality, selflessness - CNN
28 1 1 comThey laughed, they cried, they celebrated a young life lost too soon
28 1 2 Those attending Jessica Ghawi's memorial service Saturday at a San Antonio church heard numerous adjectives describing the hockey fan and aspiring sports broadcaster
28 1 3 "Spitfire
28 1 4 ""Spunky
28 1 5 ""Clumsy
28 1 6 ""Tough
28 1 7 "The descriptions punctuated a service that lauded the life of a woman killed while in pursuit of her dreams
28 1 8 Ghawi was among the 12 killed in the July 20 mass shooting at a movie theater in Aurora, Colorado
28 1 9 Dozens of others were wounded
28 1 10 Her service was one of four held Saturday for victims of the massacre
28 1 11 Matt McQuinn was remembered in Springfield, Ohio; Alex Teves was honored in Phoenix; while a private funeral was held in Illinois for John T
28 1 12  Larimer
28 1 13 Remembering the victims through photos, memoriesGhawi's family created the Jessica Redfield Sports Journalism Scholarship Fund in her name to help others who dream of pursuing careers in journalism
28 1 14 Ghawi, 24, went by the name Jessica Redfield on-air
28 1 15 Several speakers humorously recalled when Ghawi, as an intern wearing high heels, fell three times on the ice while interviewing members of the San Antonio Rampage hockey club
28 1 16 A video of the falls was shown at the service
28 1 17 Pastor Robert Emmitt of Community Bible Church said Ghawi -- despite the pain and embarrassment -- got back up
28 1 18 He called her a "strong-willed child
28 1 19 "The victim's brother, Jordan Ghawi, referring first to the suspect in the Colorado shooting, had two messages for the audience
28 1 20 "If this coward could have done this with this much hate, imagine what we can do with this much love," he said
28 1 21 "If you are putting your dreams on hold, you stop that right now
28 1 22 You chase those dreams
28 1 23 You don't know how long you have here
28 1 24 "Mom who lost daughter in shooting has miscarriageJessica Ghawi, who moved to the Denver area to pursue her career, narrowly avoided another shooting incident in Toronto just last month -- an incident that prompted her to reflect on life on her blog
28 1 25 The Toronto shooting at the Eaton Centre left one person dead and seven injured
28 1 26 "I was shown how fragile life was on Saturday
28 1 27 I saw the terror on bystanders' faces
28 1 28 I saw the victims of a senseless crime
28 1 29 I saw lives change," she wrote at the time
28 1 30 "I was reminded that we don't know when or where our time on Earth will end
28 1 31 When or where we will breathe our last breath
28 1 32 "The young woman's boyfriend, minor league hockey player Jay Meloff, said, "She drank in life and celebrated the things that made us uniquely us
28 1 33 "Tales of heroism abound from Colorado movie theater tragedyIn Ohio, McQuinn's family is still trying to make sense of his heroic death
28 1 34 McQuinn, 27, died shielding his girlfriend, Samantha Yowler, during the shooting
28 1 35 She attended Saturday's memorial service, where Quinn's portrait sat near rows of flowers in the front of Maiden Lane Church of God in Springfield
28 1 36 Herb Shaffer said during the service that his nephew's core goodness and selflessness came out during that midnight showing of "The Dark Knight Rises" in Aurora
28 1 37 "In a moment of crisis, you don't have time to think about what you're going to do, all you have time is to react," said Shaffer, who is also a pastor
28 1 38 "And we saw a picture of Matt in that moment of crisis
28 1 39 
28 1 40 
28 1 41 
28 1 42  His immediate response was to protect the one that he loved
28 1 43 "Alex Teves, 24, also died while protecting his girlfriend, Amanda Lindgren
28 1 44 More than a week later, his friends and family gathered in Phoenix to remember his spirit and life
28 1 45 Attendees, including Teves' parents, attended the memorial service in white T-shirts and blue jeans, just as Teves routinely did while in high school and beyond
28 1 46 Teves graduated in June with a master's degree in counseling psychology from the University of Denver
28 1 47 "He wasn't very vain, he was more interested in relationships," his father, Tom Teves, told reporters Saturday before entering Corpus Christi Catholic Church for the service
28 1 48 "
28 1 49 
28 1 50 
28 1 51 He put people first, always
28 1 52 "About 1,700 miles away in Crystal Lake, Illinois, Larimer received full military honors at his funeral
28 1 53 The Navy petty officer 3rd class had been in the military for about one year
28 1 54 Like his father and grandfather, the 27-year-old Larimer chose to join the U
28 1 55 S
28 1 56  Navy
28 1 57 He was serving at his first post, said his father, Scott Larimer
28 1 58 Meanwhile, a court document filed Friday showed suspect James Holmes was a patient of a University of Colorado psychiatrist before last week's attack at a movie theater that killed 12 people and wounded scores
28 1 59 The disclosure was in a request by Holmes for authorities to immediately hand over a package he sent to Dr
28 1 60  Lynne Fenton at the university's Anschutz Medical Campus
28 1 61 According to Holmes' request, the package seized by authorities under a July 23 search warrant was a protected communication
28 1 62 "The materials contained in that package include communications from Mr
28 1 63  Holmes to Dr
28 1 64  Fenton that Mr
28 1 65  Holmes asserts are privileged," said the document filed by public defenders representing Holmes
28 1 66 "Mr
28 1 67 Holmes was a psychiatric patient of Dr
28 1 68  Fenton, and his communications with her are protected
28 1 69 "Victims remembered with poignant storiesIn response, prosecutors asked for Arapahoe County District Judge William Sylvester to deny the request by Holmes, saying it contained inaccuracies including claims of media leaks by government officials that in reality may have been fabricated by news organizations
28 1 70 Sylvester granted a hearing on the request for Monday, the same day that Holmes is scheduled to be formally charged in the case
28 1 71 Eleven wounded survivors remained hospitalized Saturday at three facilities, including five in critical condition
28 1 72 One of them, Ashley Moser, underwent "an additional surgery" on Saturday morning and also suffered a miscarriage due to "the extreme trauma she sustained," her family said in a statement
28 1 73 Moser's 6-year-old daughter, Veronica, was the youngest person killed in the shooting
28 1 74 How to help the victimsShare your memories of the victims with us on CNN iReport
28 1 75

29 1 0 Theater shooting unfolds in real time on social media - CNN
29 1 1 comThe posts show how quickly life can change
29 1 2 "Everyones dressing up as Batman, im going dressed as Bruce Wayne
29 1 3 
29 1 4 
29 1 5  Albeit a short stubby unsexy Bruce Wayne #CouldntFindBatmanMaskInTime," wrote one Twitter user, identified online as Zach Eastman
29 1 6 "Going to see the final batman tonight!So EXCITED!!!" wrote another Twitter user, @DjaylaRene
29 1 7 And, in hindsight, most chillingly: "Of course we're seeing Dark Knight 
29 1 8 
29 1 9 
29 1 10  people should never argue with me
29 1 11 "Gunman kills 12 in Colorado theater shootingThose posts surfaced before the shootings early Friday morning at a late-night showing in Aurora, Colorado, of the Batman movie "The Dark Knight Rises," in which 12 people were killed and dozens more were injured
29 1 12 All three people who were quoted above appear to have been in the theater complex when a heavily armed gunman opened fire on moviegoers, according to police
29 1 13 The third post appears to be from Jessica Ghawi, who was reported dead in the shooting
29 1 14 Ghawi was a former sports-news intern at a television station in San Antonio, according to that station, Fox 29
29 1 15 "It's true, my former intern Jessica Ghawi was a victim in the shootings last night
29 1 16 She used @JessicaRedfield as her twitter handle," wrote a Twitter user identified as Mike Taylor
29 1 17 In the hours after the shooting, her friend mourned her death in real time
29 1 18 "Devastated," wrote a sports radio host in Denver, identified online as Peter Burns
29 1 19 "Lost a very close friend in the shooting last night
29 1 20 @JessicaRedfield came to Denver to pursue sports career
29 1 21 I'm shaking
29 1 22 "Aspiring sports reporter Ghawi feared dead in shootingThe horrifying posts highlight a shift in the way our society tells the story of a tragedy, and also how we react to it
29 1 23 Before Twitter, smartphones and YouTube, it would have been impossible for an event like Colorado's "Batman Massacre" to have played out for the global public in real time
29 1 24 The shooting is just the latest instance of social media being used to document a tragedy or a news event even as it is unfolding
29 1 25 A Pakistani man last year unwittingly live-tweeted the raid that killed Osama bin Laden
29 1 26 And the war in Syria is being documented in large part by citizens and members of the opposition movement who risk their lives to post YouTube videos and photos of the violence
29 1 27 NRA tweeter was 'unaware' of Colorado shooting, spokesman saysBut the social media posts about the Colorado shooting are a haunting reminder of the visceral power of first-person accounts of tragedy
29 1 28 And also a sign that society these days deals with grieving after an event like this in a much more public and immediate way than in years past
29 1 29 Reports of the 1999 Columbine school shooting, for example, which happened only 17 miles from Aurora, spread in a much different way
29 1 30 Thirteen years ago, witnesses talked to TV crews rather than uploading their stories instantly to the Internet with mobile phones
29 1 31 Shooting turns movie into surreal horror: 'This is real'Some reports from the Aurora movie theater appeared to come out as the shooting occurred
29 1 32 "Now I'm thinking it was bullets coming through the wall from 9 causing smoke and fire cracker sounds
29 1 33 #aurorashooting #batman #shootng," a Twitter user identified as Jamie Marshall wrote
29 1 34 "Never seen so many cop cars in my life
29 1 35 Its a parade of lights," wrote Isaac Ramos
29 1 36 "Everything keeps replaying in my head
29 1 37 It was so unreal," @DjaylaRene wrote
29 1 38 "I am getting ready to cry
29 1 39 So scared
29 1 40 I need a hug
29 1 41 I almost got shot 9 times
29 1 42 I had a chance to be like 50," wrote another Twitter user, @Abenistar
29 1 43 He later added: "I seen a person bleeding out their mouth and gasping for their last breath
29 1 44 This ain't right
29 1 45 #Century16Shooting
29 1 46 Thunk the world is ending
29 1 47 "Shaky YouTube videos show people screaming, crying and rushing out of the theater after the shooting, some of them with bloody wounds
29 1 48 Another video, apparently taken outside the building by a person who was in the theater next to the shooting, offers a glimpse into the mindset of a person who has just witnessed tragedy
29 1 49 The amateur videographer sounds to be at a loss for words
29 1 50 "Oh Jesus
29 1 51 July 20th, 2012
29 1 52 Aurora Century 16," he says, in a sort of real-time confessional about the event
29 1 53 "There has been a massive shooting here
29 1 54 A lot of people wounded, a lot of people dead
29 1 55 I can't really take pictures, just because I'd rather (be) helping people than wanting to take pictures of some pretty ghastly (expletive)
29 1 56 There's some guy in a gas mask apparently -- teargassed theater 9
29 1 57  We were in theater 8
29 1 58  Just lit it up
29 1 59 It hit a lot of people, a lot of younger people
29 1 60 Oh
29 1 61 It's pretty -- it's pretty bad
29 1 62 "Timeline of worst mass shootings in U
29 1 63 S
29 1 64 Officials also turned to the Internet in an effort to make sense of the events
29 1 65 The Red Cross is asking people who witnessed the shooting to tell loved ones that they were OK over social media sites like Facebook and Twitter
29 1 66 "People don't know how close you were, so help alleviate that anxiety," spokeswoman Patricia Billinger told USA Today
29 1 67 And other officials used the Internet to offer sympathy
29 1 68 "We certainly appreciate the nation's thoughts and prayers as our police department continues to investigate the terrible theater shooting tragedy that occurred today," the city of Aurora wrote on its Facebook page
29 1 69 "Our condolences go out to the victims and their family members
29 1 70 "Are you there?Share your story with us on CNN iReport and post your tributes to the victims
29 1 71 CNN's Doug Gross and Dorrine Mendoza contributed to this report

30 1 0 Colorado shooting suspect was a psychiatric patient - CNN
30 1 1 comColorado shooting suspect James Holmes was a patient of a University of Colorado psychiatrist before last week's attack at a movie theater that killed 12 people and wounded scores, according to a court document filed Friday by his public-defense lawyers
30 1 2 The disclosure was in a request by Holmes for authorities to immediately hand over a package he sent to Dr
30 1 3  Lynne Fenton at the university's Anschutz Medical Campus
30 1 4 According to Holmes' request, the package seized by authorities under a July 23 search warrant was a protected communication
30 1 5 "The materials contained in that package include communications from Mr
30 1 6  Holmes to Dr
30 1 7  Fenton that Mr
30 1 8  Holmes asserts are privileged," said the document filed by public defenders representing Holmes
30 1 9 "Mr
30 1 10 Holmes was a psychiatric patient of Dr
30 1 11  Fenton, and his communications with her are protected
30 1 12 "In response, prosecutors asked for Arapahoe County District Judge William Sylvester to deny the request by Holmes, saying it contained inaccuracies including claims of media leaks by government officials that in reality may have been fabricated by news organizations
30 1 13 Sylvester granted a hearing on the request for Monday, the same day that Holmes is scheduled to be formally charged in the case
30 1 14 Court appearance fuels theories about Colorado shooting suspectMeanwhile, 11 wounded survivors remained hospitalized Friday at three facilities, including five in critical condition
30 1 15 At Swedish Medical Center, two victims were in fair condition after multiple surgeries since the shootings, a hospital spokeswoman said
30 1 16 "Both appear to be doing well and their spirits are definitely at a higher level," said Audra Mincey, public relations manager at the medical center
30 1 17 Holmes allegedly opened fire in the theater on July 20 during the midnight premiere of the Batman movie "The Dark Knight Rises
30 1 18 "The suspect, , who identified himself to police as "the Joker," remained in custody after being ordered held without bond earlier this week, and will be formally charged on Monday
30 1 19 A group of 17 media organizations, including CNN, asked Sylvester on Friday to unseal court documents in the case, particularly affidavits for probable cause involving search warrants that already have been executed
30 1 20 Two court orders posted on a court website Thursday noted restrictions on information the University of Colorado could release about Holmes
30 1 21 The 24-year-old had recently dropped out of a Ph
30 1 22 D program in neuroscience out of the school's campus in Aurora
30 1 23 The orders, in addition to a previous one issued Wednesday aimed at "limiting pre-trial publicity" at the defendant's request, endeavor to restrict the amount of publicly available information in order to assure "the fairness of a trial
30 1 24 "Authorities discovered the package Holmes sent Fenton on Monday in a mailroom at the University of Colorado -- Anschutz Medical Campus, a law enforcement official briefed on the investigation said Wednesday
30 1 25 CBS News reported that, according to unidentified sources, "the letter was from a pent-up Holmes to one of his professors
30 1 26 ""In it, he talked about shooting people and even included crude drawings of a gunman and his victims," according to the CBS report
30 1 27 In the court request for authorities to turn over the package, Holmes cited media leaks as a violation of Sylvester's court orders
30 1 28 Prosecutors responded that there was no proof that government officials leaked any information and said the reported leaks may well have been fabricated by news organizations
30 1 29 "To put it bluntly, the People are extremely dubious of the media assertions that 'law enforcement sources' exist," said the prosecution document
30 1 30 University spokeswoman Jacque Montgomery said Friday the university had no further comment at the moment
30 1 31 Holmes had booby-trapped his sparsely furnished third-floor, one-bedroom unit apartment with more than 30 homemade grenades and 10 gallons of gasoline, a law enforcement official who viewed video showing the apartment's interior has told CNN
30 1 32 The sophisticated setup was meant to harm, or possibly kill, anyone who entered -- and tested the skills of bomb squad members charged with clearing it, the official said
30 1 33 Other tenants of the apartment building where Holmes had lived were rousted out of their apartments by police in the early hours of July 20 after the shooting
30 1 34 They were allowed to begin returning home more than five days later
30 1 35 Official: Trap in Colorado suspect's home had 30 homemade grenades, gasolineSome of the shooting victims, both in and out of hospitals, faced a difficult recovery process and the prospect of daunting medical bills
30 1 36 They include Caleb Medley, who lost an eye and suffered brain damage
30 1 37 His wife gave birth to their son Hugo Jackson Medley on Tuesday morning, and the University of Colorado Hospital said both baby and mother are doing well
30 1 38 Medley, who had been doing standup comedy routines in Denver and was working full-time at Target, had no health insurance, his brother Seth said
30 1 39 "The surgeon came and talked to us and said he'd be in ICU at least a week," said Medley's friend, Michael West, who set up a website to help take care of medical bills and the needs of Medley's family
30 1 40 By Thursday evening, it had raised more than $313,000
30 1 41 Chloe Anderson has set up a similar fund for her sister, Petra Anderson, an aspiring musician who was also shot in the head
30 1 42 In a video posted Sunday asking for funds, Chloe Anderson notes that her mother was preparing to undergo cancer treatment later this month when Friday's shooting occurred
30 1 43 "My sister's hospital bills on top of that are making the financial reality look pretty daunting," she says
30 1 44 "So that's why we are reaching out to you -- the people who have already asked us what they can do to help
30 1 45 "By Wednesday evening, that fund had received more than $184,000 with a goal of $250,000
30 1 46 Money is also streaming in to GivingFirst
30 1 47 org,which is accepting donations for the shooting victims and their relatives
30 1 48 By Tuesday, the amount had reached almost $2 million, Gov
30 1 49  John Hickenlooper said
30 1 50 "The needs will be great and we look forward to seeing the fund grow exponentially," he said
30 1 51 "This money will help those impacted by this tragedy begin to recover and rebuild their lives
30 1 52 "Hickenlooper said donors include Warner Bros
30 1 53  and Legendary Pictures, co-producers of "The Dark Knight Rises
30 1 54 "Sources at Warner Bros
30 1 55  studios told CNN the company made a "substantial" donation
30 1 56 Warner Bros
30 1 57 , a subsidiary of CNN's parent company Time Warner, would not divulge how much money it was giving out of respect for the victims, the sources said
30 1 58 United Airlines said Friday it was working with the American Red Cross to help pay for flights of family members of victims
30 1 59 "All of us were impacted by these events, and we want to help in any way we can," said a brief statement by the company
30 1 60 Several hospitals were also making efforts to minimize the financial burden
30 1 61 Children's Hospital Colorado said in a statement it will use its charity program and donations to cover medical expenses for victims who don't have insurance, as well as waive co-pays and deductible-related expenses for those with insurance
30 1 62 HealthOne, the health care system that includes the Medical Center of Aurora and Swedish Medical Center, pledged to "eliminate personal financial responsibility for hospital charges as appropriate
30 1 63 "And Denver Health said it will evaluate each patient "on a case-by-case basis" and discount bills by 70% for those unable to pay
30 1 64 Gun owners debate in wake of Aurora tragedyCNN's Tom Cohen, Randi Kaye, Ed Payne, Tom Watkins, Holly Yan, Drew Griffin, Kathleen Johnston, Scott Zamost, Elwyn Lopez, Carol Cratty, Poppy Harlow, Dana Ford, Breeanna Hare, Alta Spells, Ed Lavandera, Nick Valencia and Jessica Jordan contributed to this report

31 1 0 Colorado movie shooting suspect charged with murder - CNN
31 1 1 comCentennial, Colorado Colorado movie shooting suspect James Holmes was charged Monday with 24 counts of first-degree murder -- two counts for each of the 12 people killed in the shooting
31 1 2 Twelve of the murder counts cite "deliberation," and 12 cite "extreme indifference" to the value of human life
31 1 3 The 24-year-old former doctoral student also was charged with 116 counts of attempted murder -- two for each of the 58 moviegoers wounded in the attack
31 1 4 Finally, he was charged with one count of felony possession of explosive devices and one count related to the use of an assault weapon, a shotgun and a handgun during the incident
31 1 5 The 142 counts are all in connection with the July 20 massacre in the Century Aurora 16 multiplex minutes into a midnight screening of "The Dark Knight Rises
31 1 6 "Shackled around his wrists and ankles, Holmes was escorted into Arapahoe County Courthouse by two sheriffs deputies
31 1 7 Five other sheriffs deputies were standing in the courtroom
31 1 8 Court appearance fuels theories about Colorado shooting suspectIn his first court appearance last week, Holmes appeared dazed and did not speak
31 1 9 During Monday's hearing, meanwhile, he seemed calm and frail, sitting at the right edge of the defense table with his dyed-orange hair matted on top, its roots dark
31 1 10 For a while, he stared blankly at the judge's bench but appeared to be aware of what was going on
31 1 11 When the judge asked him whether he understood why his attorneys were asking for more time before a hearing, he said softly, "Yes
31 1 12 "About half of the approximately 120 seats in the courtroom were filled with victims or their family members; more watched on video in an overflow room
31 1 13 One young man in the front row of the courtroom leaned forward and stared at Holmes without averting his gaze throughout the 45-minute proceeding
31 1 14 Read the charges (PDF)Another observer, her left arm and leg in bandages, sat slumped in her seat
31 1 15 Around her wrist was a hospital wristband
31 1 16 "It was very important to come today to see him as who he was," MaryEllen Hansen told reporters outside the courthouse
31 1 17 "I really wanted an opportunity to watch his gestures (and) study him as much as I could
31 1 18 "Her niece's 6-year-old daughter, Veronica Moser-Sullivan, was the youngest person killed in the rampage
31 1 19 Hansen's niece, Ashley Moser, faces a long recovery after being paralyzed in her lower half and miscarrying after the shooting
31 1 20 "I got a sense that he was very aware of what was going on," Hansen said of Holmes
31 1 21 "He had an expression and kind of a persona of evilness to him
31 1 22 But he looked very sane to me, he really did
31 1 23 "Asked if she favors the death penalty, the retired school principal said, "I'm a Christian and I do believe that he should probably be locked away and live with what he did every day of his life
31 1 24 "Background of suspect full of contrastsArapahoe County District Attorney Carol Chambers said last Monday that it will take time for prosecutors to decide whether or not they will pursue the death penalty, since they'd first want to get input from victims and their relatives
31 1 25 Authorities have remained silent about a possible motive in the case
31 1 26 A court document filed Friday revealed that Holmes was a patient of a University of Colorado psychiatrist before the attack
31 1 27 The disclosure was made in a filing by Holmes' public defenders requesting that authorities hand over a package he sent to Dr
31 1 28  Lynne Fenton at the university's Anschutz Medical Campus, where he had been studying neuroscience before announcing earlier this month that he was withdrawing from the program
31 1 29 The package seized by authorities under a July 23 search warrant should remain confidential, protected by the doctor-patient relationship because "Holmes was a psychiatric patient of Fenton," the request said
31 1 30 In response, prosecutors asked Arapahoe County District Judge William Sylvester to deny Holmes' request, saying it contained inaccuracies including claims of media leaks by government officials that in reality may have been fabricated by news organizations
31 1 31 The package is expected to be the focus of a status hearing set for August 9
31 1 32 Prosecutors say they will begin turning over thousands of pages of discovery in the next couple of days
31 1 33 The defense says they need this information to prepare for the hearing
31 1 34 Warning signs of violence: What to doDuring the week of November 12, attorneys expect a preliminary hearing and an evidence hearing that will include several days of testimony
31 1 35 As Monday's hearing unfolded, 10 survivors remained hospitalized, three of them in critical condition
31 1 36 But there was some progress: The day began at the University of Colorado Hospital at Aurora, for instance, with three in critical, one in serious and one in fair condition and ended with two in critical and three in fair condition
31 1 37 Meanwhile, those affected continued to come to grips with the horror
31 1 38 On Saturday alone, memorial services were held for four people killed in the massacre including two men -- Matt McQuinn from Ohio and Alex Teves from Arizona -- who died shielding their girlfriends from gunfire
31 1 39 Closer to Aurora, which is just east of Denver, people worked to make sense of what happened and support one another
31 1 40 For some, that includes making sure the shooting suspect knows that they are stronger, better and united
31 1 41 "The man was a coward
31 1 42 We're here to show that we have strength and that we're willing to fight back," said Don Lader, after attending Monday's court hearing
31 1 43 "He looked defeated," Lader added about Holmes, "and he knows that he's not the one with power anymore -- that's us
31 1 44 "Remembering the victims through stories, photosCNN's Ed Lavandera contributed to this report

32 1 0 Analysis: Why gun controls are off the agenda in America - CNN
32 1 1 comWhat is it about Americans and guns?How much time do you have?"I can tell you that I don't think there's any other developed country in the world that has remotely the problem we have," New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg said after the shooting rampage in Colorado
32 1 2 There are an estimated 270 million guns in the hands of civilians in the United States, making Americans the most heavily armed people in the world per capita
32 1 3 Yemen, a tribal nation with no history of strong central government or the rule of law, comes in a distant second
32 1 4 From Washington to the well-stocked shelves of Walmart stores nationwide, guns are regarded in the United States as a commonplace if controversial consumer item for millions of law-abiding hunters, collectors and citizens concerned about their safety
32 1 5 They are also in the hands of thousands of killers too; a Washington-based anti-gun lobby says those guns shoot more than 100,000 people a year
32 1 6 In 2010, there were more than 30,000 deaths caused by firearms when the number of homicides, suicides and accidental deaths are tallied
32 1 7 Read: Why has Obama largely steered clear of gun debate?America's collective memory -- of the Wild West in the 1800s, the assassinations of John F
32 1 8  Kennedy and Martin Luther King half a century ago and the front-page news from last week -- is marked time and time again by guns
32 1 9 "It's undeniable," writes Clayton Cramer, author of "Armed America: the Remarkable Story of How and Why Guns Became as American as Apple Pie
32 1 10 " "Guns are at the center of much of America's history, its legends, and its horrors
32 1 11 "There were guns in America long before the America we know today was even born
32 1 12 Early settlers in several states were required by law to own and maintain weapons as a matter of collective defense
32 1 13 By the time the United States was established, its citizens had taken up arms not only against their Native American neighbors but the army of their own king
32 1 14 Their new constitution reflected that in its Bill of Rights, declaring that "A well regulated militia being necessary to the security of a free state, the right of the people to keep and bear arms shall not be infringed
32 1 15 "For more than two centuries, that remained an important but largely overlooked guarantee, subjected to a modest series of controls
32 1 16 But in 2008 and 2010, landmark Supreme Court rulings gave that constitutional right sweeping new power, dramatically diminishing the authority of state and local governments to limit gun ownership
32 1 17 Gun-friendly lawmakers have been active, too
32 1 18 Roughly half of the 50 U
32 1 19 S
32 1 20  states have adopted laws allowing gun owners to carry their guns openly in most public places
32 1 21 About as many states have "stand your ground" laws that allow people to kill if they come under threat, even, in some cases, if they can escape the threat without violence
32 1 22 The laws are being driven by politics, and the politics are being driven by groups such as the National Rifle Association
32 1 23 Once a relatively modest organization of gun enthusiasts and hunters, it has become one of the most powerful political groups in the country
32 1 24 The Washington Post estimates that the NRA succeeded in helping elect four out of every five candidates it endorsed in the most recent congressional election
32 1 25 In addition to that extraordinary impact in Congress, it has been working to overturn gun-control laws in the courts
32 1 26 The NRA and other gun-rights groups have allied themselves with the Republican Party and, especially, a sector of the American public suspicious of government intrusions into private life and often flatly hostile to Washington
32 1 27 Read Dana Bash: For Democrats, gun politics are bad politics"When they tell you that a government ban on certain firearms will somehow make you safer, don't you believe it, not for a second, because it's a lie just like the lies they've told you before," NRA CEO Wayne LaPierre told a recent gathering of his members
32 1 28 "Their laws don't work
32 1 29 "Poll results suggest most Americans wouldn't agree
32 1 30 CNN and Gallup surveys going back years suggest that Americans are split between those who approve of current gun-control laws and respondents who would like to see them made more restrictive
32 1 31 Americans who'd like no controls at all are a small minority
32 1 32 But even after the rampage in Colorado, American attitudes and laws aren't likely to change much
32 1 33 Last year's nearly fatal shooting of congresswoman Gabrielle Giffords didn't move her state or federal colleagues to adopt any new gun control measures
32 1 34 Both President Barack Obama and Republican challenger Mitt Romney issued statements in the hours after the Colorado shootings, and Sunday, Obama flew to the state to visit with shooting victims and their families
32 1 35 But neither proposed any changes to American attitudes toward guns
32 1 36 "You know, soothing words are nice, but maybe it's time that the two people who want to be president of the United States stand up and tell us what they are going to do about it, because this is obviously a problem across the country," said New York's Bloomberg, who is both a declared "independent" politically and a vocal proponent of gun control
32 1 37 America is not unique
32 1 38 Norwegians are marking the first anniversary of a shooting massacre that took the lives of 69 people at a summer camp outside of Oslo
32 1 39 Eight more people were that day killed by a bomb in the Norwegian capital itself
32 1 40 The confessed killer is awaiting the verdict of his trial
32 1 41 But America seems to be the place the whole world thinks of when apparently ordinary people use guns for grotesque acts of violence
32 1 42 America stands alone in its historic and cultural attachment to guns
32 1 43 America stands armed
32 1 44 Do you own a gun?Tell us why
32 1 45 Opinion: Mass murder and powerful firearmsOpinion: Gun control or carry permits won't stop mass murderOpinion: Fear drives opposition to gun control
